{{Use New Zealand English|date=August 2012}} {{Use dmy dates|date=July 2011}} {{Infobox field hockey player |name = Amanda Hooper |image = Canterbury earthquake memorial opening 101.jpg |caption = The inscription for Hooper on the [[Canterbury Earthquake National Memorial]] |birth_date = 1980 |birth_place = [[Southland, New Zealand|Southland]], New Zealand |death_date = {{death date|df=y|2011|02|22}} (aged 30) |death_place = [[Christchurch]], New Zealand |height = |position = |currentclub = |youthclubs1 = |youthyears1 = |clubs1 = |years1 = |caps(goals)1 = |nationalteam1 = [[New Zealand women's national field hockey team|New Zealand]] |nationalyears1 = 2001–2003 |nationalcaps(goals)1 = 40 |updated = |medaltemplates = }} '''Amanda Jane Hooper''' (née '''Christie''', 1980 – 22 February 2011) was a female professional [[field hockey]] player from New Zealand. She died in one of the office buildings that collapsed in the February [[2011 Christchurch earthquake]] at age 30.
Amanda Christie was born in [[Southland, New Zealand|Southland]] in 1980 and grew up in [[Waikaia]] on her family's farm. She was head girl at [[Gore High School]] in 1998; her motivation for success stemmed from her father's death four years earlier.<ref name="EQ bio">{{cite news|title=Amanda Hooper|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/the-press/news/christchurch-earthquake-2011/12-51/our-people/the-victims/profiles/4710794/Amanda-Hooper|accessdate=14 July 2016|work=[[The Southland Times]]|date=27 February 2011}}</ref> She was married to [[Richard Hooper (umpire)|Richard Hooper]] and had two girls with him<ref name="EQ bio" /> who at the time of her death were two and four years old.<ref name="the bereaved">{{cite news |last1=van Beynen |first1=Martin |title=The lives of the bereaved <!-- Print title shown; online title was "The earthquake bereaved will remember and recover in their own ways" --> |url= http://www.stuff.co.nz/the-press/news/christchurch-earthquake-2011/76794061/the-earthquake-bereaved-will-remember-and-recover-in-their-own-ways |accessdate=7 February 2017|work=[[The Press]] |date=20 February 2016 |page=A6–A7}}</ref>
She was a member of the national women's squad ''[[New Zealand women's national field hockey team|The Black Sticks]]'' from 2001 to 2003, with a total of 40 caps.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.hockeynz.co.nz/documents/Black%20Sticks/WOMEN/20101018%20Black%20Sticks%20Women%20(Caps%20Only).pdf | title=New Zealand Hockey Representatives – Women | publisher=Hockey NZ}}{{dead link|date=July 2016}}</ref> In 2003, she was nominated for World Junior Player of the Year.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.starcanterbury.co.nz/sport/news/ex-coach-tips-hat-to-warm-driven-athlete-who-loved/3942539/ |title=Ex-coach tips hat to warm, driven athlete who loved life and hockey |work=[[The Star (Christchurch)|The Star]] |date=1 March 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724194412/http://www.starcanterbury.co.nz/sport/news/ex-coach-tips-hat-to-warm-driven-athlete-who-loved/3942539/ |archivedate=24 July 2011 }}</ref> She participated in the [[2002 Commonwealth Games]] in [[Manchester]], England, where the New Zealand women came [[Hockey at the 2002 Commonwealth Games|fourth]]. She competed in the [[2002 Women's Hockey World Cup]] where New Zealand came eleventh.<ref name="Herald bio" /> Locally, she played 55 games for [[Canterbury, New Zealand|Canterbury]], and was a member of Carlton [[Redcliffs]].<ref name="EQ bio" />
Hooper lived in [[Rolleston, New Zealand|Rolleston]] and worked for Marac Finance as an account manager.<ref name="Herald bio">{{cite news|title=Amanda Hooper|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10711717|accessdate=14 July 2016|work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]|date=11 March 2011}}</ref> Her company was based at the [[PGC building]] in the [[Christchurch Central City]] that collapsed in the 2011 Christchurch earthquake.<ref name="EQ bio" /> On 11 March 2011, Christchurch police confirmed that Hooper was one of the victims of the earthquake.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/christchurch-earthquake/4758247/Christchurch-police-name-14-more-earthquake-victims |title=Christchurch police name 14 more earthquake victims |date=11 March 2011 |work=[[Stuff.co.nz]] |accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref> [[Ian Rutledge]], her coach for two years, described her as having a "warm and caring nature" and "one of the hardest-training athletes he had come across in his coaching career".<ref name="Herald bio" /> Her former team, Carlton Redcliffs, awards the Amanda Hooper Award and has retired her number from their women's team in her memory.<ref>{{cite web|title=Amanda Hooper Award 2015|url=http://www.carltonredcliffs.com/small-gallery-article/amanda-hooper-award-2015/152964/346465/|publisher=Carlton Redcliffs Hockey Club|accessdate=14 July 2016}}</ref>
