background:lightgreen" |April 15–May 16 |Operation Mountain Lion takes place in coordination with [[Operation Jacana#Operation Ptarmigan|Operation Ptarmigan]] (a subsidiary operation of [[Operation Jacana]]), US forces, [[Australian SAS]] and other Coalition special forces and conventional forces aimed to find and deny control of the [[Gardez]] and Khost regions in Afghanistan to al-Qaeda terrorists and Taliban fighters. The operation resulted in small but fierce firefights with fighters who had infiltrated across the Pakistan border, [[Major general (United States)|Maj.Gen]] [[Franklin L. Hagenbeck]] said that al-Qaeda still possessed much of its leadership and command-and-control structure.<ref name="ReferenceA">Clements, Frank A., '' Conflict in Afghanistan: An Encyclopedia (Roots of Modern Conflict)'', ABC-CLIO, 2003 {{ISBN|1851094024}} {{ISBN|978-1851094028}}</ref><ref name=Neville>Neville, Leigh, '' Special Forces in the War on Terror (General Military)'', Osprey Publishing, 2015 {{ISBN|978-1-4728-0790-8}}</ref> |- style="background:lightgreen" |April 16–July 9 |[[Operation Jacana]] takes place: In the aftermath of Operation Anaconda, British, US, Australian and Norwegian forces conduct a series of operations aimed at finding and eliminating remaining al-Qaeda and Taliban in [[Khost province]] and Paktia Province in Afghanistan. 11 enemy combatants were killed and 9 more captured, a large number of weapons cashes were also captured and/or destroyed; the results of the operations also showed that al-Qaeda and the Taliban had abandoned a large scale presence in the region.<ref name="ReferenceA"/> |- style="background:lightgreen" |May 14 |Members of the [[Lashkar-e-Taiba|Lashkar-e-Taiba (LeT)]] carried out an [[2002 Kaluchak massacre|attack]] on a tourist bus in India, killing 31 and injuring 47. |- style="background:#EA3C53" |May 16 |Operation Eagle Assist ends. |- style="background:goldenrod" |October 7 |[[Operation Enduring Freedom – Horn of Africa]] begins.<ref>{{cite journal|date=May–June 2008|title=Intelligence Center offers MTTs on cultural awareness, intel topics|journal=Infantry Magazine|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0IAV/is_3_97/ai_n27966901/|accessdate=April 3, 2010}}</ref> |- style="background:khaki" |October 8 |The [[Faylaka Island attack]] in [[Kuwait]] killed 1 U.S. Marine and injured another. |- style="background:yellowgreen" |October 12 |[[Jemaah Islamiyah|Jemaah Islamiyah (JI)]] and other al-Qaeda terrorists carried the [[2002 Bali bombings|Bali bombings]] in [[Indonesia]] which killed 202 and injured 209 people. |- style="background:lightgrey" |October 16 |The [[Iraq Resolution]] is enacted after being passed by the United States Congress, authorizing military action against Iraq. |- style="background:lightgrey" |November 8 |The United Nations Security Council unanimously adopted [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 1441|Resolution 1441]]: offering [[Ba'athist Iraq|Saddam Hussein's regime]] "a final opportunity to comply with its disarmament obligations" that had been set out in several previous resolutions. |- style="background:khaki" |November 26 |The [[Central Intelligence Agency]] begins a series of ongoing Predator drone strikes on [[Islamic Jihad of Yemen|Al-Qaeda in Yemen]] and al-Qaeda in Saudi Arabia.<ref name="google2811">{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=7nsuAAAAIBAJ&sjid=7YkFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2811,1484648&dq=targeted-killing&hl=en|author=Walter Pincus |title= U.S. Says Yemen Aided Missile Strike|work=The Daily Gazette|date=November 26, 2002 |accessdate=May 20, 2010}}</ref> |- style="background:goldenrod" |November 28 |Al-Qaeda carried out the [[2002 Mombasa attacks|Mombasa attacks]] in [[Kenya]], killing 13 and injuring 80 people. |}
== 2003 == [[File:SaddamSpiderHole.jpg|thumb|[[Saddam Hussein]] being pulled from his hideaway in [[Operation Red Dawn]], 13 December 2003.]] {| class="wikitable" |- ! Dates !! Events |- style="background:lightgrey" |January 3–April 12 |[[List of anti-war organizations|Anti-war groups]] across the world organized [[Protests against the Iraq War|public protests against war with Iraq]]. About 36 million people across the globe took part in almost 3,000 protests.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Callinicos |first=Alex |date=March 19, 2005 |title=Anti-war protests do make a difference |journal=Socialist Worker |issue=1943 |url=http://www.socialistworker.co.uk/article.php?article_id=6067 |accessdate=April 3, 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060321084247/http://www.socialistworker.co.uk/article.php?article_id=6067 |archivedate=March 21, 2006 |df= }}</ref> |- style="background:lightgreen" |January 27 |US Special forces and Afghan forces were searching a compound in the mountains near [[Spin Boldak]], Kandahar province, Afghanistan when they were engaged by 3 fighters loyal to the [[Hezb-e Islami Gulbuddin|Hezb-e Islami Gulbuddin (HIG)]] (that was designated a terrorist group on February 19), killing one, wounding and capturing another. After they interrogated the prisoner they divulged the location of 80 other HIG fighters in the mountains, they called in air support from [[Rockwell B-1 Lancer|B-1 bombers]], [[General Dynamics F-16 Fighting Falcon|F-16]]s, [[Lockheed AC-130|AC-130]]s and [[Boeing AH-64 Apache|Apache]] helicopters, before Coalition troops moved in. At least 18 HIG fighters were killed, it was the largest engagement since Operation Anaconda.<ref name="ReferenceA"/><ref name="Hizb-i-Islami Gulbuddin HIG">{{cite web|url=http://www.understandingwar.org/hizb-i-islami-gulbuddin-hig|title=Hizb-i-Islami Gulbuddin (HIG)|publisher=Institute For The Study Of War}}</ref> |- style="background:lightgrey" |February 5 |[[Colin Powell]] addressed a plenary session of the United Nations Security Council, stating categorically that [[Saddam Hussein]] was working to obtain key components to produce nuclear weapons. |- style="background:white" |February 19 |The HIG was designated a terrorist group-for several months its leader, [[Gulbuddin Hekmatyar]], had been trying to consolidate the remnants of al-Qaeda and the Taliban into one anti-Coalition force.<ref name="ReferenceA"/><ref name="Hizb-i-Islami Gulbuddin HIG"/> |- style="background:khaki" |March 20 |The '''[[Iraq War]]''' begins with the [[2003 invasion of Iraq|Invasion of Iraq]]. President [[George W. Bush]] refers to it as "the central front in the [[Iraq War and U.S. Global War on Terrorism|War on Terror]]".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov/news/releases/2003/09/20030909.html|title=A Central Front in the War on Terror, From the President's speech to the Nation|last=Bush|first=George W.|date=September 9, 2003|accessdate=April 3, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov/news/releases/2006/08/20060821.html|title=Press Conference by the President; White House Conference Center Briefing Room|last=Bush|first=George W.|date=August 21, 2006|accessdate=April 3, 2010|location=Washington DC, United States}}</ref> |- style="background:khaki" |March 28–30 |[[Operation Viking Hammer]] takes place: US Forces and Iraqi Kurdish forces eliminated [[Ansar al-Islam|AAI]] terrorists and its allies who had occupied parts of Iraqi Kurdistan, killing around 150-200 Ansar al Islam terrorists and 100 more terrorist-allied fighters were killed, Iraqi Kurdish forces suffered 30 killed, 23 wounded. |- style="background:khaki" |April 19 |The US [[Joint Special Operations Command]]'s [[Joint Special Operations Command Task Force in the Iraq War#History as Task Force 20|Task Force 20]] captured [[Muhammad Zaidan|Mohammed Abbas]], the leader of the [[Palestine Liberation Front|Palestine Liberation Front (PLF/PLO)]], in [[Baghdad]], Iraq. US authorities cited Abbas's presence in Baghdad as evidence that Iraq had been harboring international terrorists<ref name="Neville"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1456489/Abu-Abbas.html|title=Abu Abbas|publisher=the Telegraph|date=11 March 2004}}</ref> |- style="background:orangered" |May 16 |[[Salafia Jihadia]]-a Salafi jihadist militant group with links to al-Qaeda and associated with the [[Moroccan Islamic Combatant Group|GICM]]-carried out the [[2003 Casablanca bombings|Casablanca bombings]] in Morocco, killing 45 and injuring over 100 people. |- style="background:white" |Spring–September 20 or November |Small groups of foreign jihadists that infiltrated Iraq following the invasion, as well as nationalist [[Sunni Islam|Sunni]] Iraqis, merged with the remnants of AAI who had fled to [[Iran]] and/or infiltrated Iraq to form [[Jamaat Ansar al-Sunna|Ansar al-Sunnah (AAS)]].<ref name="ReferenceB">[[Malcolm Nance|Nance, Malcolm W.]], ''[[The Terrorists of Iraq|The Terrorists of Iraq: Inside the Strategy and Tactics of the Iraq Insurgency 2003-2014]]'', CRC Press, 2014 {{ISBN|1498706894}} {{ISBN|978-1498706896}}</ref><ref name="Chalk, Peter 2012"/> |- style="background:yellowgreen" |August 5 |JI and al-Qaeda terrorists carried out the [[2003 Marriott Hotel bombing|Marriott Hotel bombing]] in Indonesia which killed 12 and injured 150 people. |- style="background:lightgreen" |October 2 |Pakistani forces (allegedly in a joint mission with US forces) attacked an al-Qaeda hideout in [[South Waziristan]] killing [[Hasan Mahsum]], the leader of the [[Turkistan Islamic Party|East Turkestan Islamic Movement (ETIM)]] and 7 others. |- style="background:white" |October 23 |The leader of the Algerian terrorist faction [[Salafist Group for Preaching and Combat|Salafist Group for Preaching and Combat (GSPC)]], [[Hassan Hattab]], was replaced by [[Nabil Sahraoui]], who declared the groups allegiance to al-Qaeda.<ref name="bbc oct03">[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/3207363.stm Algerian group backs al-Qaeda], BBC News, 23 October 2003</ref> |- style="background:khaki" |October 31 |Members of the 22nd SAS Regiment and Delta Force, supported by other US troops, conducted Operation Abalone: Its target was a [[Demographics of Sudan|Sudanese]] jihadist-who was believed to be facilitating the arrival of Islamist terrorists into Iraq-in compounds/dwellings on the outskirts of [[Ramadi]], Iraq. The operation was a success; the Sudanese jihadist is believed to have been killed along with a dozen other terrorists, 4 foreign jihadists were also captured-finding some of the first actual proof of an internationalist jihadist movement that emerged in post-invasion Iraq. 1 [[United Kingdom Special Forces|UKSF]] soldier was killed and several others wounded.<ref>Urban, Mark, ''Task Force Black: The Explosive True Story of the Secret Special Forces War in Iraq '', St. Martin's Griffin, 2012 {{ISBN|978-1-250-00696-7}}, p.20–21, p.26–31, p.88</ref><ref>Neville, Leigh, '' Special Forces in the War on Terror (General Military)'', Osprey Publishing, 2015 {{ISBN|978-1-4728-0790-8}}, p.195</ref> |- style="background:khaki" |November 15 and 20 |The [[2003 Istanbul bombings|Istanbul bombings]] in Turkey by al-Qaeda killed 57 and injured around 700 people. |- style="background:khaki" |December 13 |[[Operation Red Dawn]] takes place: [[Saddam Hussein]] is found and captured by U.S. forces in [[Ad-Dawr]], Iraq.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,105706,00.html | work=Fox News | title=Saddam Captured 'Like a Rat' in Raid – Fox News | date=October 21, 2011}}</ref> |- style="background:yellowgreen" |Unknown |[[Noordin Mohammad Top]], a senior terrorist in JI, is said to have split from the group and formed [[Tanzim Qaedat al-Jihad|al-Qaeda in the Malay Archipelago]].<ref name="Who was Noordin Mohammed Top">{{cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/asia-pacific/2009/08/2009885495465108.html|title=Who was Noordin Mohammed Top?|publisher=Al Jazeera|date=19 September 2009}}</ref> |}
== 2004 == [[File:M113 Iraq 041001-F-2034C-017.jpg|thumb|U.S. Army [[M106 mortar carrier]]s of the [[1st Infantry Division (United States)|1st Infantry Division]] leaving [[Samarra]] after conducting an assault there during the [[Battle of Samarra (2004)|Battle of Samarra]], 1 October 2004.]] [[File:US Navy 041108-M-8205V-006 An air strike is called in on a suspected insurgent hideout at the edge of Fallujah, Iraq by U.S. Marines assigned K Company, 3rd Battalion, 5th Marine Regiment, 1st Marine Division, during the openin.jpg|thumb|An airstrike destroys a suspected insurgent hideout in [[Fallujah]] during the [[Second Battle of Fallujah]], 8 November 2004.]] {| class="wikitable" |- ! Dates !! Events |- style="background:yellowgreen" |February 27 |[[Abu Sayyaf|Abu Sayyaf (ASG)]] carryout the [[2004 SuperFerry 14 bombing|SuperFerry 14 bombing]] in the Philippines, killing 116 people. |- style="background:cornflowerblue" |March 11 |The [[Madrid train bombings]] in [[Spain]] kill 191 and injure over 2,000 people, the attack was carried out by an al-Qaeda cell. |- style="background:lightgreen" |March 16 |'''[[War in North-West Pakistan]]''' begins with the [[Battle of Wana]] between Pakistani forces and al-Qaeda. |- style="background:lightgreen" |March 23 |The Battle of Wana ends, Pakistani forces lost 49 soldiers killed, 11 soldiers captured, 33 soldiers wounded, whilst al-Qaeda suffered 55 killed and 150 more captured. |- style="background:khaki" |April 4–May 1 |The [[First Battle of Fallujah]] takes place: Following the [[2004 Fallujah ambush|Fallujah ambush]] on March 31, the US military launched an operation to regain control of [[Fallujah]] from [[Jama'at al-Tawhid wal-Jihad|Jama'at al-Tawhid wal-Jihad (JTJ)]] terrorists and other insurgents. On April 9 US troops were ordered to halt their offensive, after having cleared at least 25% of the city and declare a ceasefire after political pressure from the [[Iraqi Governing Council]] and the negative media coverage by ''[[Al Jazeera]]'' and ''[[Al Arabiya]]'' of the battle effecting public opinion. By the end of April, US forces gave control of the city to the Fallujah Brigade-a Sunni security force formed by the CIA; 27 US troops were killed in the operation, whilst 184–228 terrorists and insurgents were killed.<ref>Martin, Guss, '' The SAGE Encyclopedia of Terrorism, Second Edition'', 2011, SAGE Publications {{ISBN|1-4129-8016-X}} {{ISBN|978-1-4129-8016-6}}</ref><ref name="Urban, Mark p.63">Urban, Mark, ''Task Force Black: The Explosive True Story of the Secret Special Forces War in Iraq '', St. Martin's Griffin, 2012 {{ISBN|1-250-00696-1}} {{ISBN|978-1-250-00696-7}}, p.63</ref><ref>Samuel-Azran, Tal, '' Al-Jazeera and US War Coverage'', 2010, Peter Lang Publishing Inc, {{ISBN|1-4331-0864-X}} {{ISBN|978-1-4331-0864-8}}</ref><ref>Tucker, Spencer C., '' U.S. Conflicts in the 21st Century: Afghanistan War, Iraq War, and the War on Terror'', 2015, Greenwood Press, {{ISBN|1-4408-3878-X}} {{ISBN|978-1-4408-3878-1}}</ref><ref name="Donald P 2013">Wright Dr. Donald P. and Reese Colonel Timothy R., '' On Point II: Transition to the New Campaign: The United States Army in Operation IRAQI FREEDOM, May 2003-January 2005'', 2013, CreateSpace Independent Publishing Platform, {{ISBN|1-4944-0647-0}} {{ISBN|978-1-4944-0647-9}}</ref> By September, the Brigade dissolved and turned over all its weapons and soldiers to terrorist and insurgent groups in the city.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/08/05/AR2007080501299_pf.html | work=The Washington Post | title=Weapons Given to Iraq Are Missing | first=Glenn | last=Kessler | accessdate=2 May 2010}}</ref><ref name="Urban, Mark p.63" /> |- style="background:khaki" |April 24 |The [[Georgia Train and Equip Program]] ends |- style="background:khaki" |May 29 |Members of al-Qaeda and its affiliates carryout the [[2004 Khobar massacre|Khobar massacre]] in [[Saudi Arabia]], which kills 22 and injures 25 people. |- style="background:lightgreen" |June 18 | The [[United States government]], led by the CIA's [[Special Activities Division]], begins a series of ongoing attacks on targets in northwest [[Pakistan]] using drones ([[unmanned aerial vehicles]]). These attacks sought to defeat the Taliban and Al-Qaeda militants who were thought to have found a safe haven in Pakistan.<ref name="The CIA's Silent War in Pakistan">[http://www.time.com/time/printout/0,8816,1900248,00.html The CIA's Silent War in Pakistan], TIME, June 1, 2009</ref> |- style="background:orangered" |June 20 |The leader of the GSPC, [[Nabil Sahraoui]], was killed along with 3 of his lieutenants/aides in a shootout with the [[Algerian army]] during a "vast anti-terror operation" involving 3,000 soldiers in a sweep of wooded mountains in [[Bejaia Province]] in Algeria.<ref>[http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/world/archives/2004/06/21/2003175948 ''Algerian armed forces say rebel leader is killed'' Taipei Times (Reuters report), 21 June 2004]</ref><ref name=fnews2004>{{cite news|title=Algerian Military Says Terror Leader Killed|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,123181,00.html|accessdate=24 January 2013|newspaper=Fox News|date=20 June 2004|agency=AP}}</ref> |- style="background:cornflowerblue" |September 1–3 |The [[Beslan school siege]] takes place: 34 terrorists belonging to [[Riyad-us Saliheen]] took over a school in [[Beslan]], [[North Ossetia-Alania]], Russia, taking 1,100 people as hostages. Russian security forces eventually stormed the building with the use of tanks, armored vehicles, heavy weapons and attack helicopters; the rescue operation killed 334 hostages and 10 civilians and injured approximately 783; 31 terrorists were killed and over 10 of the security force was killed. |- style="background:yellowgreen" |September 9 |The [[2004 Australian Embassy bombing in Jakarta|bombing of the Australian Embassy in Jakarta]], Indonesia, by JI killed 8 and wounded 150 people. |- style="background:khaki" |October 1–3 |The [[Battle of Samarra (2004)|Battle of Samarra]] takes place: In the run up to the [[Iraqi parliamentary election, January 2005|January 2005 Iraqi election]], the [[Iraqi Interim Government]] and the Coalition began a campaign to clear [[Samarra]] and Fallujah of JTJ and other insurgent's control, thereby ending the violence towards security forces and civilians and securing the election. US and Iraqi forces liberated Samarra after 3 days of fighting, resulting in 127 terrorists and other insurgents killed with a further 60 wounded and 128 captured, Coalition forces lost 1 killed and 8 wounded.<ref name="Donald P 2013"/> |- style="background:white" |October 17 |The JTJ became known as [[Tanzim Qaidat al-Jihad fi Bilad al-Rafidayn|Tanzim Qaidat al-Jihad fi Bilad al-Rafidayn-commonly known as al-Qaeda in Iraq (AQI)]], when its leader, [[Abu Musab al-Zarqawi]], allegiance to Osama bin Laden's al-Qaeda network. |- style="background:khaki" |November 7–December 23 |The [[Second Battle of Fallujah]] takes place: US, UK and Iraqi forces launch an offensive to liberate Fallujah from [[Tanzim Qaidat al-Jihad fi Bilad al-Rafidayn|AQI]] and AAS terrorists, as well as other insurgents and terrorists, killing 1,200–1,500 enemy combatants, whilst 1,500 more were captured, coalition forces suffered 107 killed and 613 wounded.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-29984665|title=Iraq's hardest fight: The US battle for Falluja 2004|publisher=BBC|date=10 November 2014}}</ref> |- style="background:khaki" |November 8–16 |The [[Battle of Mosul (2004)|Battle of Mosul]] takes place after AQI terrorists and other insurgents began carrying out coordinated attacks and ambushes in an attempt to take over the city, US, Iraqi security forces and Kurdish forces counterattacked, retaking terrorist and insurgent held areas, which ended major fighting on November 16, however the western area and parts of the eastern city remained in insurgent hands. The US lost 4 killed, whilst Iraqi forces suffered 116 killed and 5,000 deserted, 1 British and 1 Turkish security contractors were killed; 71 terrorists and insurgents were confirmed killed.<ref>http://www.understandingwar.org/sites/default/files/reports/Iraq%20Report%208.pdf, p.9</ref><ref name="ReferenceC">Mockaitis, Thomas R., '' The Iraq War Encyclopedia '', ABC-CLIO, 2013 {{ISBN|0-313-38062-7}} {{ISBN|978-0-313-38062-4}}</ref> |}
== 2005 == [[File:Russell square ambulances.jpg|thumb|Emergency vehicles at Russell Square after the [[7 July 2005 London bombings]].]] [[File:USMC-051107-M-2147S-005.jpg|thumb|U.S. Marines from the [[2nd Marine Division]] and an Iraqi soldier engage insurgents during [[Operation Steel Curtain]], a subsidiary operation of [[Operation Sayeed]], 7 November 2005.]] {| class="wikitable" |- ! Dates !! Events |- style="background:khaki" |January 1 |The [[Georgia Sustainment and Stability Operations Program]] begins. |- style="background:khaki" |May 8–19 |[[Battle of Al Qaim|Operation Matador]] takes place: In an effort to stem the flow of terrorists and insurgents entering Iraq from [[Syria]], US Marines fought and secured the [[Al Ubaidi|Ubaydi]] and the town of Ramana, suffering 9 killed and 40 wounded, whilst the AQI terrorists and other insurgents lost an estimated 144 killed and 90 captured. US forces did not garrison the towns and insurgents resumed control over the city.<ref name="ReferenceC"/><ref>Wastl-Walter, Doris, '' The Ashgate Research Companion to Border Studies'', 2011, Routledge, {{ISBN|0-7546-7406-1}} {{ISBN|978-0-7546-7406-1}}</ref><ref>W Estes, Kenneth, ''U.S. Marines in Iraq, 2004–2005: Into the Fray: U.S. Marines in the Global War on Terror'', 2011, CreateSpace Independent Publishing Platform {{ISBN|1-4700-9507-6}} {{ISBN|978-1-4700-9507-9}}</ref><ref>Schlosser, Dr. Nicholas J., '' U.S. Marines In Battle: Al-Qaim, September 2005-March 2006 [Illustrated Edition]'', Tannenberg Publishing, 2014</ref> |- style="background:cornflowerblue" |July 7 |The [[7 July 2005 London bombings|London bombings]] kill 52 people and injure 700 more.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.salon.com/news/feature/2005/07/08/blowback/index.html|title= The time of revenge has come|last=Cole|first=Juan|date=July 8, 2005|work=Salon|accessdate=April 3, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Croft|first=Stuart|title=Culture, Crisis and America's War on Terror|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=New York, NY|date=October 2, 2006|pages=232–234|isbn=0-521-68733-0}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Wade|first=Marianne|author2=Maljevic, Almir |title=A War on Terror?|publisher=Springer|location=New York, NY|date=November 18, 2009|edition=1|pages=336|isbn=0-387-89290-7}}</ref> |- style="background:khaki" |July 23 |[[Operation Marlborough]] takes place: members of the [[Special Boat Service|British Special Boat Service]], with support from elements of the 22nd SAS Regiment and U.S. military assaulted an AQI safehouse in southern [[Baghdad]] and killed 3 terrorists who were about to carryout major suicide bombings. |- style="background:khaki" |July–December 22 |[[Operation Sayeed]] takes place: known as an "umbrella" operation-where a number of subsidiary operations took place under it. The operations took place in [[Al Anbar Governorate]] in Iraq and were aimed at significantly removing AQI's presence from the Western Euphrates River Valley; to ensure there was a secure "climate" and "environment" to conduct a [[Iraqi constitutional referendum, 2005|referendum in October]] and [[Iraqi parliamentary election, December 2005|national elections in December 2005]]; and to secure control of the Iraqi border to the Iraqi people. The operation was a success-causing significant disruption to AQI's organization that had a lasting effect across Al-Anbar Governorate; in addition to destroying much of the AQI leadership and command-and-control functions, the operation also ensured the safety and maximum participation of Iraqi citizens in the constitutional referendum and national elections. The US lost 54 killed and 324 wounded, Iraqi security forces lost 16 killed and 89 wounded; the terrorists and insurgents lost between 727 and almost 1,000 killed; between 2,308 and almost 4,000 captured; and 64 wounded. |- style="background:khaki" |September 1–18 |The [[Battle of Tal Afar (2005)|Battle of Tal Afar]] takes place: US and Iraqi forces carried out a military operation to eliminate AQI terrorists and other insurgents from [[Tal Afar]] in Iraq, which the terrorists were using as a staging ground for moving foreign fighters into Iraq since early 2005. Coalition forces succeeded in their objectives at the cost of US forces losing 6 killed, 52 Wounded and Iraqi forces losing 15 killed and 36 wounded. Terrorists and insurgent groups lost 163 killed and between 295–700 captured. |- style="background:yellowgreen" |October 1 |JI carried out the [[2005 Bali bombings|Bali Bombings]] in Indonesia, which killed 20 and injured more than 100 people. |- style="background:khaki" |November 9 |The [[2005 Amman bombings|Amman bombings]] in [[Jordan]] kill 60 and injured 115 people, AQI carried out the attack. |- style="background:khaki" |November 26 |The [[Christian Peacemaker hostage crisis]] in Iraq begins when 4 members of the [[Christian Peacemaker Teams]] were abducted in Baghdad by members of the terrorist group [[Swords of Righteousness Brigade]]-a small offshoot of possibly [[Islamic Army in Iraq|IAI]], AAI, Army of Islam, or a cover name for their abduction cells, or freelance cash criminal abductors.<ref>Urban, Mark, ''Task Force Black: The Explosive True Story of the Secret Special Forces War in Iraq '', St. Martin's Griffin, 2012 {{ISBN|978-1-250-00696-7}}</ref><ref name="ReferenceB"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.trackingterrorism.org/group/swords-righteousness-brigade|title=Swords of Righteousness Brigade|publisher=Terrorism Research & Analysis Consortium}}</ref> |}
== 2006 == [[File:Zarqawi dead us govt photo.jpg|thumb|Corpse of [[Abu Musab al-Zarqawi]], the leader of [[Tanzim Qaidat al-Jihad fi Bilad al-Rafidayn|AQI]], who was killed in a U.S. airstrike in Hibhib, 7 June 2006.]] {| class="wikitable" |- ! Dates !! Events |- style="background:white" |January 15 |AQI was one of five or six other Sunni insurgent groups that formed the [[Mujahideen Shura Council (Iraq)|Mujahideen Shura Council (MSC)]] that embraced the same [[Salafi jihadism|Salafist ideology]] as AQI.<ref>Urban, Mark, ''Task Force Black: The Explosive True Story of the Secret Special Forces War in Iraq '', St. Martin's Griffin, 2012 {{ISBN|1250006961}} {{ISBN|978-1250006967}}, p.118,</ref> |- style="background:lightgreen" |March |[[DEVGRU]] operators and [[75th Ranger Regiment (United States)|US Army Rangers]] carried out an operation allegedly under the codename: Operation Vigilant Harvest. Their target was an al-Qaeda training camp in [[North Waziristan]] in Pakistan, they were flown across the Afghan-Pakistan border. The force killed as many as 30 terrorists, including the [[Chechens|Chechen]] camp commandant Imam Asad. The operation has been falsely credited to the [[Special Services Group|Pakistani Special Service Group]].<ref>Neville, Leigh, '' Special Forces in the War on Terror (General Military)'', Osprey Publishing, 2015 {{ISBN|978-1-4728-0790-8}}, p.232-233</ref> |- style="background:khaki" |March 23 |The Christian Peacemaker hostage crisis in Iraq is brought to a successful conclusion when members of the 22nd SAS Regiment raided a house in western Baghdad and rescued the 3 remaining hostages, the raid was part of Operation Lightwater: The operation initiated by [[Task Force 88 (anti-terrorist unit)#Task Force Black/Knight|Task Force Knight]] (the British special forces task force in Iraq) supported by JTF2 and Canadian and US intelligence units. |- style="background:khaki" |April 16 |[[Operation Larchwood 4]] takes place: Members of the 22nd SAS Regiment, supported by US forces, carried out a raid on an AQI-occupied farmhouse [[Yusufiyah]] in Iraq, the target for the operation was to capture a mid-level terrorist leader. The SAS suffered 5 wounded but killed 5 terrorists and captured their target and another senior AQI terrorist, whom revealed around May 20 information that eventually led to discovery of Abu Musab al-Zarqawi, the leader of AQI. |- style="background:khaki" |April 28–December 25 |AQI (from mid-October it was reformed as [[Islamic State of Iraq|ISI]]) succeeded in carrying out a coordinated offensive to take control of [[Diyala Governorate]] in Iraq, where Abu Musab al-Zarqawi, the leader of AQI and the [[Mujahideen Shura Council (Iraq)|Mujahideen Shura Council (MSC)]] designated the Governorate as his Islamic caliphate with [[Baquba]] as its capital (where he based his headquarters). Baquba fell on December 25, leading to the start of the [[Diyala campaign]]. |- style="background:goldenrod" |June 4 |Islamist insurgents begin [[Advance of the Islamic Courts Union|taking over]] large parts of Somalia. |- style="background:khaki" |June 7 |2 U.S. [[General Dynamics F-16 Fighting Falcon|F-16C]] Jets carryout an airstrike on a farmhouse/safehouse in Hibhib a village outside [[Baquba]] in Iraq, killing AQI's leader Abu Musab al-Zarqawi.<ref>Urban, Mark, ''Task Force Black: The Explosive True Story of the Secret Special Forces War in Iraq '', St. Martin's Griffin, 2012 {{ISBN|1-250-00696-1}} {{ISBN|978-1-250-00696-7}}, p.148-149, p.159-160</ref> |- style="background:khaki" |June 17–November 15 |The [[Battle of Ramadi (2006)|Second Battle of Ramadi]] takes place: U.S. and Iraqi forces mostly drive AQI (from mid-October it was reformed as ISI) and other Sunni insurgents out of their de facto capital: Ramadi, 750 militants were killed, the US lost 80+ killed and 200+ wounded whilst the Iraq lost 30 troops and policemen killed. |- style="background:khaki" |July 9–October 24 |[[Operation Together Forward]] takes place: US and Iraqi forces, supported by British forces carryout the operation to counter AQI's (later reformed as ISI) determination to make its attacks on [[Baghdad]] a central role in its plans to undermine the new Iraqi government, as well as reduce the sectarian violence in the city in order to strengthen the Iraqi government and security forces. The operation failed, terrorists and other insurgents infiltrated back into cleared areas, the violence escalated and Iraqi security forces appeared insufficient. US forces suffered 101 killed and 1 captured, Iraqi security forces lost 197 killed; whilst over 400 terrorists and other insurgents were killed or captured. |- style="background:goldenrod" |July 20 |The '''[[War in Somalia (2006–09)]]''' begins when U.S. backed Ethiopian troops invaded Somalia to support the [[Transitional Federal Government|Somali Transitional Government]] against Islamist insurgents |- style="background:khaki" |August 17 |[[The Second Battle of Habbaniyah]] begins: Taking place in the urban sprawl between Fallujah and Ramadi, one of the most vicious and protracted battles of the Iraq war took place. |- style="background:white" |Mid-October |Al-Qaeda announced the creation of [[Islamic state of Iraq|Islamic state of Iraq (ISI)]] with Ramadi as its capital.<ref>Urban, Mark, ''Task Force Black: The Explosive True Story of the Secret Special Forces War in Iraq '', St. Martin's Griffin, 2012 {{ISBN|1250006961}} {{ISBN|978-1250006967}}, p.183</ref> replacing the MSC and its AQI. |- style="background:khaki" |November 5 |[[Saddam Hussein]] is sentenced to death by hanging, he is hanged on December 30 at [[Camp Banzai|Camp Justice]] in [[Baghdad]], Iraq. |- style="background:white" |December |Around this time, [[Al-Shabaab (militant group)|Al-Shabaab]]-previously serving as the [[Islamic Courts Union]]'s military wing-emerged as an independent organization after breaking away from the ICU, which had by then splintered into several smaller factions after its defeat by Somali [[Transitional Federal Government|TFG]] and Ethiopian forces.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.stanford.edu/group/mappingmilitants/cgi-bin/groups/view/61|title=Mapping Militant Organizations|publisher=Stanford University|date=20 February 2016}}</ref><ref>Model, David, ''From Slaves to Oil'' AuthorHouse, 2014, {{ASIN|B00L9DHJ4M}}</ref> |}
== 2007 == [[File:Buried IED blast in 2007 in Iraq.jpg|thumb|A US Army [[Stryker]] following an [[Improvised explosive device|IED]] blast near a village outside [[Baghdad]], during [[Operation Imposing Law]], 15 April 2007.]] [[File:Arrowhead ripper.jpg|thumb|U.S. soldiers from the [[2nd Infantry Division (United States)|2nd Infantry Division]] clearing a village on the outskirts of [[Baqubah]] as part of Operation Arrowhead Ripper during the [[Battle of Baqubah]], 19 June 2007.]] [[File:OH-58D Kiowa providing air support for Marne Torch.jpg|thumb|An [[Bell OH-58 Kiowa|OH-58D Kiowa]] provides air support to coalition troops during [[Operation Marne Torch#Marne Torch I|Operation Marne Torch I]], as part of [[Operation Phantom Thunder]], 28 June 2007.]] {| class="wikitable" |- ! Dates !! Events |- style="background:goldenrod" |January 5–12 |The [[Battle of Ras Kamboni]] takes place: Ethiopian and the Somali TFG forces supported by US AC-130 gunship fought for control of [[Ras Kamboni]], Somalia, from ICU, [[Oromo Liberation Front|OLF]], al-Qaeda operatives and other affiliated militants and to eliminate them. 16 enemy combatants were killed and 44 civilians were killed<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2007/01/the_battle_of_ras_ka.php|title=The Battle of Ras Kamboni|publisher=long war journal|date=8 January 2007}}</ref> |- style="background:khaki" |January 6–9 and January 24 |The [[Battle of Haifa Street]] takes place: Iraqi troops killed 30 Sunni insurgents at a fake checkpoint, in retaliation 27 Shias were killed and the rest threatened, on January 8, US and Iraqi troops launched an offensive to clear out the area of ISI terrorists and insurgents, killing or capturing 70 terrorists and other insurgents, 25 others were detained. The area was temporarily cleared but insurgents reinfiltated the area, on January 24, US and Iraqi forces conducted Operation Tomahawk Strike II to clear the area, approximately 65 insurgents and terrorists were killed and captured. 20 Iraqi soldiers were killed during both engagements.<ref>Tucker, Spencer C., '' U.S. Conflicts in the 21st Century: Afghanistan War, Iraq War, and the War on Terror'', 2015, Greenwood Press, {{ISBN|1-4408-3878-X}} {{ISBN|978-1-4408-3878-1}}</ref><ref>Kimberly, Kagan, ''The Surge: A Military History'', 2009, Encounter Books, {{ISBN|1-59403-249-1}} {{ISBN|978-1-59403-249-3}}</ref><ref>Tucker, Spencer C., ''The Encyclopedia of Middle East Wars [5 Volumes]: The United States in the Persian Gulf, Afghanistan, and Iraq Conflicts'', 2010, ABC-CLIO Ltd, {{ISBN|1-85109-947-6}} {{ISBN|978-1-85109-947-4}}</ref> |- style="background:khaki" |January 11 |Delta Force operators and other US forces [[U.S. raid on the Iranian Liaison Office in Arbil|raided the Iranian Liaison Office]] in [[Irbil]], Iraq, intelligence from the raid produced evidence that Iran had connections with AAS in an effort to undermine the coalition efforts in Iraq.<ref>Urban, Mark, ''Task Force Black: The Explosive True Story of the Secret Special Forces War in Iraq '', St. Martin's Griffin, 2012 {{ISBN|1-250-00696-1}} {{ISBN|978-1-250-00696-7}}, p.209-210</ref> |- style="background:white" |January 28 |The GSPC changed its name to [[al-Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb|al-Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb (AQIM)]]. |- style="background:darksalmon;" |February 6 |[[Operation Enduring Freedom – Trans Sahara]] begins.<ref name=OEF-TS-GLOBALSECURITY>{{cite web|title=Operation Enduring Freedom – Trans Sahara (OEF-TS) Operation Juniper Shield|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/ops/oef-ts.htm|publisher=GlobalSecurity.org|accessdate=February 6, 2007 }}</ref> |- style="background:orangered" |February 11 |The [[11 April 2007 Algiers bombings|Algiers bombings]] in [[Algeria]] by al-Qaeda kill 33 and injure over 130 people. |- style="background:khaki" |February 14 |The Second Battle of Habbaniyah ends in a Coalition victory after causing the flow of supplies and terrorists into the major cities of Iraq to dry up permanently; some 14 [[United States Marine Corps|US Marines]] and 37 insurgents were killed. |- style="background:khaki" |February 14–November 24 |Coalition forces carryout [[Operation Imposing Law]] to secure Baghdad from ISI terrorists and other insurgent's control ((which was estimated as high as 70%) and reducing the sectarian violence. The operation later became part of Operation Phantom Thunder in June when US and Iraqi forces cleared the northern and southern flanks of the city; by November the operation was declared a success. The violence was reduced and most of the city cam under coalition control. 872 Coalition members were killed and over 1,200 terrorists and insurgents were killed.<ref name="ReferenceC"/><ref>Great Britain: Parliament: House of Commons: Defence Committee, '' UK Land Operations in Iraq 2007: First Report of Session 2007-08 – Report, Together with Formal Minutes, Oral and Written Evidence (HC)'', 2007, Stationery Office Books, {{ISBN|0-215-03759-6}}, {{ISBN|978-0-215-03759-6}}</ref><ref>Cordesman, Anthony H. and Davies, Emma R., '' Iraq's Insurgency and the Road to Civil Conflict (Praeger Security International)'', 2007, Praeger Security International, {{ISBN|0-313-34997-5}}, {{ISBN|978-0-313-34997-3}}</ref> |- style="background:khaki" |March 10–August 19 |The [[Battle of Baqubah]] in Iraq took place: US and Iraqi forces began clearing [[Buhriz]] and eastern half of Baqubah of insurgents and ISI terrorists from their de facto capital. On 18 June, as part of [[Operation Phantom Thunder]], US forces commenced Operation Arrowhead Ripper an offensive operations from the west, the operation ended on August 19 with the city largely being secured, although the insurgent presence remained in the city and surrounding areas, it was not in large numbers. US forces lost 31 killed and 55 wounded, Iraqi forces lost 13 killed and 15 wounded; over 227 terrorists and other insurgents were killed and 100 more were detained. |- style="background:white" |March |The [[Al-Qaeda Kurdish Battalions|al-Qaeda Kurdish Battalions (AQKB)]] formed.<ref>[https://web.stanford.edu/group/mappingmilitants/cgi-bin/groups/print_view/395#note2 Mapping Militant Organizations, Al Qaeda Kurdish Battalions]</ref> |- style="background:khaki" |May 20–September 7 |The '''[[2007 Lebanon conflict|Lebanon conflict]]''' takes place: The Lebanese security forces began fighting [[Jund al-Sham]] and [[Fatah al-Islam]], the conflict ended in a Lebanese victory, with Lebanese forces suffering 170-179 killed and 406-500 wounded, 238 terrorists were killed and a further 233 wounded, 65 civilians were also killed, whilst [[United Nations Interim Force in Lebanon|UN forces in Lebanon]] lost 6 soldiers killed and 2 wounded. |- style="background:goldenrod" |May 31–June 1 |It was reported that following clashes between the local militia or police and 35 Islamist militants who arrived in the area by boat-which forced the militants into nearby hills or to escape by sea, the [[USS Chafee]] bombarded an ICU camp in the mountains near [[Bargal]] in Somalia. Al-Qaeda terrorists and the remnants of the ICU and other Islamists militants were gathered at the camp, "actionable intelligence" gathered by U.S. Special Operations Forces and local tribal leaders suggested that [[Fazul Abdullah Mohammed]], head of intelligence for the ICU and a leader of al Qaeda's East Africa network, and other High Valued Targets were in the area. Some of the Islamists escaped by boat or inland,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/6714473.stm|title=US attacks Somali 'militant base'|publisher=BBC|date=2 June 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2007/06/us_naval_task_force.php|title=U.S. Naval Task Force strikes at 1998 al Qaeda Embassy bomber|publisher=Long War Journal|date=2 June 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-usa-somalia-qaeda-idUKN0136819520070602|title=U.S. Navy strike reported on Qaeda suspect in Somalia|publisher=reuters|date=2 June 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/us-forces-somalia-kill-saleh-ali-nabhan-commando/story?id=8569619|title=EXCLUSIVE: US Launches Military Strike in Somalia Against al Qaeda Target|publisher=ABC news|date=14 September 2009}}</ref> 5 militia and/or police were wounded whilst a dozen Islamists were killed. |- style="background:khaki" |June 16–August 14 |[[Operation Phantom Thunder]] took place: [[Multi-National Force-Iraq]] carryout out major offensive operations across Iraq against ISI terrorists and other insurgents and jihadists, resulting in a strategic coalition victory by occupying and ejecting the insurgents from their strongholds in Northern [[Babil Governorate|Babil]], eastern Anbar, Diyala Governorate and the southern outskirts of Baghdad. Coalition forces also conducted intelligence raids against ISI and Iranian-backed cells nationwide, with emphasis on cells in Baghdad, Diyala, and central and northern Iraq. The US suffered 140 troops killed, 220 Iraqi security forces and 20 killed allied Iraqi militia killed; terrorists and other insurgents lost 1,196 killed and 6,702 captured. |- style="background:khaki" |August 15 |[[Operation Phantom Strike]] begins: Following up the success of Operation Phantom Thunder, Coalition forces in Iraq carried out operations aimed at disrupting the ISI and other terrorist and insurgent networks across the country, targeting terrorists and extremists fleeing Baghdad and other key cities with particular focus on remaining ISI terrorists and Iranian-supported insurgent groups. |- style="background:khaki" |October 1 |The Diyala campaign in Iraq ends in a Coalition victory due to the combination of the Coalition victories in the Battle of Baqubah, Operations Phantom Thunder and Operation Phantom Strike-where in August and September, [[Operation Phantom Strike#Operation Lightning Hammer I & II|Operation Lightning Hammer I & II]] took place respectively, as part of Operation Phantom Strike which defeated ISI (particularly the elements that fled from Baqubah) and other terrorist cells seeking safe haven throughout the Diyala River Valley. 106 US servicemen were killed, 300 Iraqi security forces were killed and 22 allied Iraqi militia were killed, Over 1,070 terrorists and other insurgents were killed and 500 captured. |- style="background:lightgreen" |October 5–December 8 |The [[First Battle of Swat]] took place after more than 3,000 Pakistani troops were sent to [[Swat, Pakistan|Swat Valley]] and [[Shangla District|Shangla]] in [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa|Khyber-Pakhtunkhwa Province]], Pakistan, to confront [[Tehrik-e-Taliban Pakistan|TTP]] and the TNSM, resulting in more than killing more than 290 terrorists and capturing 143 more. Pakistani forces suffered 18 killed and 48 captured. |- style="background:white" |October 7 |[[Dokka Umarov]], the [[President of Ichkeria]] of [[Chechen Republic of Ichkeria]] (an unrecognized pro-independence movement that controlled most of [[Chechnya]] in Russia) abolished the movement announced the creation of the terrorist group [[Caucasus Emirate]] and declared himself its Emir. |- style="background:white" |November or December |AAS formally acknowledged being derived from AAI, and reverted to using that name.<ref name="Chalk, Peter 2012"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://counterterrorismblog.org/2007/12/ansar_alsunnah_acknowledges_re.php |archive-url=http://arquivo.pt/wayback/20091013162709/http://counterterrorismblog.org/2007/12/ansar_alsunnah_acknowledges_re.php |dead-url=yes |archive-date=2009-10-13 |title=Ansar al-Sunnah Acknowledges Relationship with Ansar al-Islam, Reverts to Using Ansar al-Islam Name |publisher=Counterterrorism Blog |date= |accessdate=2012-08-08}}</ref> |- style="background:white" |December |The existence of the [[Tehrik-i-Taliban Pakistan|Tehrik-i-Taliban Pakistan (TTP)]] was officially announced under the leadership of [[Baitullah Mehsud]]. |}
