lley]] takes place: U.S. Aircraft supporting U.S. Special forces, as well as Afghan special forces raided a fortified town in Shok Valley of [[Nuristan Province]] in Afghanistan, occupied by HIG in an attempt to eliminate Gulbuddin Hekmatyar. The raid failed to eliminate him, U.S. forces suffered multiple wounded, ANA suffered 2 killed and multiple wounded. |- style="background:lightgreen" |June 2 |The [[2008 Danish embassy bombing in Islamabad|Danish embassy bombing in Islamabad]] in Pakistan, by al-Qaeda killed between 6-8 people and injured over 20. |- style="background:lightgreen" |July 13 |The [[Battle of Wanat]] took place: between 200-500 militants from the Taliban, al-Qaeda and HIG attacked an outpost in Nuristan province in Afghanistan, garrisoned by US and Afghan troops, the attack was repulsed, 9 US soldiers and 15 more wounded, 4 Afghan soldiers were wounded and at least 40 Taliban fighters killed during the assault.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2008/07/joint_al_qaeda_and_t.php|title=Joint al Qaeda and Taliban force behind Nuristan base attack|publisher=long war journal|date=14 July 2008}}</ref> |- style="background:khaki" |July 29–August 11 |[[Operation Augurs of Prosperity]] took place, US and Iraqi forces following up Operation Phantom Phoenix's success in Iraq's Diyala province the Operation aimed to clear the last remnants of ISI terrorists and other insurgents and terrorists from the Governorate. The operation was a success, with Iraqi security forces having achieved half of the goals set for the operation, with 15 terrorists and other insurgents killed and 800 captured, Iraqi Security forces lost 51 killed and [[Sons of Iraq|Awakening Councils]] losing 7 killed. |- style="background:lightgreen" |August 7 |The [[Battle of Bajaur]] begins: Pakistani forces launch an offensive to retake, [[Bajaur]] in Khyber-Pakhtunkhwa Province, Pakistan, from TTP, Al-Qaeda and the TNSM. |- style="background:lightgreen" |August 18 |The [[Uzbin Valley ambush]] takes place when French, Afghan and US troops were ambushed by HIG and Taliban insurgents in [[Kabul province]], Afghanistan, the coalition troops with air support and reinforcements eventually defeated the terrorists and insurgents. French forces lost 10 killed and 24 wounded, whilst Afghan forces lost 4 wounded; the terrorists and insurgents lost between 13-80 killed with another 30 wounded. |- style="background:goldenrod" |August 20–22 |The [[Battle of Kismayo (2008)]] takes place: Al-Shabaab terrorists, allied with local Islamist militias<ref name="Al Shabaab After Kismayo">{{cite web|url=https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/al-shabaab-after-kismayo|title=Al Shabaab After Kismayo|publisher=Critical Threats|date=3 October 2012}}</ref> that were formerly of the ICU, captured [[Kismayo|the port]] in Somalia. |- style="background:white" |September 11 |The [[Cyberwarfare]] section of JSOC shut down every jihadist Website that was known to them.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/top-secret-america-a-look-at-the-militarys-joint-special-operations-command/2011/08/30/gIQAvYuAxJ_story.html|title='Top Secret America': A look at the military's Joint Special Operations Command|publisher=Washington post|date=2 September 2011}}</ref> |- style="background:khaki" |September 17 |The [[Islamic Jihad of Yemen]] carryout the [[2008 attack on the American Embassy in Yemen|attack on the American Embassy in Yemen]], killing 6 and injuring 12 people. |- style="background:khaki" |October 26 |The [[2008 Abu Kamal raid|Abu Kamal raid]] takes place: [[United States Special Operations Forces|U.S. SOF]] cross into Syria via helicopter and eliminated [[Abu Ghadiya]] who was primarily involved in al-Qaeda's logistic effort in Iraq and assisted in smuggling weapons, money and fighters across the Syria-Iraq border and several other militants. |- style="background:lightgreen" |November 26–29 |The [[2008 Mumbai attacks|Mumbai attacks]] in India by LeT terrorists kill 156-164 and injure 293-600+ people |}
== 2009 == [[File:Pakistani forces - Flickr - Al Jazeera English.jpg|thumb|Pakistani soldiers at an emplacement in the [[Swat Valley]], during the [[Second Battle of Swat]], 22 May 2009.]] [[File:Flickr - The U.S. Army - Red, White, and Blue.jpg|thumb|Coffins of soldiers killed in the [[2009 Fort Hood shooting]] being loaded aboard an aircraft for flight to [[Dover Air Force Base]], 6 November 2009.]] {| class="wikitable" |- ! Dates !! Events |- style="background:white" |January |Al-Qaeda in Yemen/Islamic Jihad of Yemen and al-Qaeda in Saudi Arabia merged to form [[Al-Qaeda in the Arabian Peninsula|Al-Qaeda in the Arabian Peninsula (AQAP)]]. |- style="background:goldenrod" |January 30 |The '''[[War in Somalia (2006–09)]]''' ends after Ethiopian forces withdraw from Somalia. |- style="background:goldenrod" |January/February |The '''[[War in Somalia (2009–present)]]''' begins. |- style="background:lightgreen" |February 28 |The Battle of Bajaur ends: Pakistani forces killing 1,500 terrorists and wounding 2,000 more, whilst the Pakistanis lost 97 killed, 404 wounded and 5 captured, 176+ tribesmen were also killed. |- style="background:cornflowerblue" |April 16 |The '''[[Insurgency in the North Caucasus]]''' begins. |- style="background:lightgreen" |April 26–June 14 |[[Operation Black Thunderstorm]] takes place: The Pakistani military captures a number of districts in Khyber-Pakhtunkhwa Province in Pakistan, from TTP and TNSM, killing 1,475 terrorists and capturing 114 more, whilst the Pakistani's lost over 150 killed, 95 captured (18 rescued) and 317 wounded. |- style="background:white" |Late April |The Leader of the Caucasus Emirate announced the revival of the Riyad-us Saliheen (having not display any activity for more than four years) as [[Riyad-us Saliheen Brigade of Martyrs]] that was led by [[Said Buryatsky]]. |- style="background:lightgreen" |May 16–July 15 |As part of the [[Operation Black Thunderstorm#Operation Rah-e-Rast|third phase of Operation Black Thunderstorm]], the [[Second Battle of Swat]] takes place: Pakistani forces fought for control of Swat Valley in Pakistan, against TTP, TNSM and [[Lashkar-e-Islam|Lashkar-e-Islam (LeI)]] terrorists, eventually returning it to government control, killing 2,088 terrorists whilst the Pakistanis lost 168 killed, 454 wounded. |- style="background:lightgreen" |June 19–December 12 |[[Operation Rah-e-Nijat]] takes place: The aim of the operation by the Pakistani military was to regain control of South Waziristan in Pakistan, from the TTP, IMU, [[Islamic Jihad Union|Jama'at al-Jihad al-Islami/IJU]] (an IMU splinter faction), al-Qaeda and other foreign jihadists terrorists, the operation was a success, ground forces killed 619 terrorists and captured 83 more, whilst losing approximately 200 killed and 600 wounded. |- style="background:forestgreen" |July 26 |The '''[[Boko Haram insurgency]]''' begins. |- style="background:lightgreen" |August 5 |A U.S. drone strike on a house in Zangara, Khyber Paktunkhwa, Pakistan, killed Baitullah Mehsud, the leader of the TTP. |- style="background:lightgrey" |August 6 |Newly elected [[Obama administration]] has stopped using the phrase "war on terror";<ref>Foon Rhee, "[http://www.boston.com/news/politics/politicalintelligence/2009/12/cheney_blasts_o.html Cheney blasts Obama on Christmas Day plane scare]", ''Boston Globe, 30 December 2009.</ref> [[John O. Brennan|John Brennan]] announces that the U.S. is "at war with al Qaeda", not involved in a "global war on terror"<ref>Toby Harnden, "[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/barackobama/5990566/Barack-Obama-adviser-rejects-global-war-on-terror.html Barack Obama adviser rejects 'global war on terror]'", ''Telegraph'', 7 August 2009.</ref> instead using the term OCO (Overseas Contingency Operations).<ref name="neville">{{cite book |last1=Neville |first1= Leigh |title=Special Forces in the War on Terror |publisher= Osprey Publishing |year=2015 |isbn= 978-1-4728-0790-8}}p.280</ref> |- style="background:lightgreen" |August 27 |A US drone strike in South Waziristan, Pakistan, killed [[Tohir Yoʻldosh]] the leader of the IMU. |- style="background:lightgreen" |September 1-November 30 |The [[2009 Khyber Pass offensive|Khyber Pass offensive]] takes place: Pakistani forces launch an offensive to clear the LeI terrorists in and near the [[Khyber Pass]] in Khyber-Pakhtunkhwa Province, Pakistan. |- style="background:yellowgreen" |September 17 |Noordin Mohammed Top, the leader of al-Qaeda in the Malay Archipelago, was killed following a nine-hour siege of a house in [[Surakarta|Solo]], [[Central Java]], Indonesia, by [[Detachment 88]] of the [[Indonesian National Police]], four other suspected terrorists were killed.<ref name="Who was Noordin Mohammed Top"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.trackingterrorism.org/group/al-qaeda-malay-archipelago|title=al Qaeda in the Malay Archipelago|publisher=TRAC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/indonesia/6201033/Indonesia-police-claim-to-have-killed-terrorist-Noordin-Top.html |title= Indonesia: police claim to have killed terrorist Noordin Top |publisher= The Telegraph |date= 17 September 2009}}</ref> |- style="background:goldenrod" |October 1–7 |Al-Shabaab terrorists with members of the [[Ras Kamboni Brigades]], an Islamist insurgent group (due to ruptures within the group, one faction of the Brigade-led by [[Hassan Abdullah Hersi al-Turki]]-had begun to align itself with al-Shabaab) [[Battle of Kismayo (2009)|captured Kismayo]] in Somalia, following fighting with [[Hizbul-Islam]] militants that controlled the port.<ref name="news.bbc.co.uk">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/8491329.stm|title=Somali Islamists al-Shabab 'join al-Qaeda fight'|publisher=BBC|date=1 February 2010}}</ref><ref name="Ras Kamboni Brigade">{{cite web |url= http://web.stanford.edu/group/mappingmilitants/cgi-bin/groups/view/487 |title= Ras Kamboni Brigade |publisher= Stanford University |date= 23 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2009/10/turf_war_in_kismayo.php|title=Turf war in Kismayo|publisher=Long War Journal|date=1 October 2009}}</ref> |- style="background:lightgreen" |October 10–11 |[[Operation Janbaz]] by 10 TTP and [[Lashkar-e-Jhangvi|Lashkar-e-Jhangvi (LeJ)]] terrorists killed 12 Pakistani servicemen and 2 civilians, 9 terrorists were killed and 1 captured. |- style="background:#EA3C53" |November 5 |The [[2009 Fort Hood shooting|Fort Hood shooting]] in the United States kills 13 and injures 33. |}
== 2010 == {| class="wikitable" |- style="background:white" |February 1 |Al-Shabab declares an alliance with al-Qaeda, aligning itself with the terrorists groups global militant campaign; the faction of the Ras Kamboni Brigades led by Hassan Abdullah Hersi al-Turki completely broke away from Hizbul Islam and officially joined Al Shabaab.<ref name="Somalia profile - Timeline">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-14094632|title=Somalia profile - Timeline|publisher=BBC|date=4 September 2017}}</ref><ref name="news.bbc.co.uk"/><ref name="Ras Kamboni Brigade"/> |- style="background:cornflowerblue" |March 2 |Said Buryatsky, the leader of the terrorist group Riyad-us-Saliheen Brigade of Martyrs, was killed during a [[Federal Security Service|FSB special forces]] raid in the village of Ekazhevo in [[Ingushetia]], Russia. A total of 8 terrorists were killed and 10 more captured.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/russia/7393272/Russian-Bin-Laden-killed-by-Moscows-special-forces.html|title=Russian 'Bin Laden' killed by Moscow's special forces|publisher=the Telegraph|date=7 March 2010}}</ref> |- style="background:khaki" |April 18 |[[Iraqi Special Operations Forces|ISOF]] troops, supported by US troops, carried out a night-time raid on a terrorist safe house near [[Tikrit]] in Iraq, the ISOF surrounded the building and called on them to surrender, instead the terrorists fired on them, they returned fire and assaulted the building. The ISOF killed [[Abu Ayyub al-Masri]] and [[Abu Omar al-Baghdadi]], the leaders of ISI, 16 others were also arrested. A US [[Sikorsky UH-60 Black Hawk|UH-60 Blackhawk]] helicopter supporting the mission crashed killing a US Army Ranger and wounding the aircrew.<ref>Neville, Leigh, '' Special Forces in the War on Terror (General Military)'', Osprey Publishing, 2015 {{ISBN|978-1-4728-0790-8}}, p.226</ref><ref>[http://www.foxnews.com/world/2010/04/19/iraqi-al-qaeda-leader-killed-countrys-intelligence-team-pm-maliki-says/ "2 Most Wanted Al Qaeda Leaders in Iraq Killed by U.S., Iraqi Forces"] FoxNews, 19 April 2010.</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2010/04/19/us-iraq-violence-alqaeda-idUSTRE63I3CL20100419|title=Al Qaeda's top two leaders in Iraq have been killed, officials said Monday, in a strike the United States called a "potentially devastating blow" but whose impact analysts said may be limited|author=Waleed Ibrahim|publisher=Thomson Reuters}}</ref> |- style="background:goldenrod" |August 23 |The [[Battle of Mogadishu (2010–11)]] began in Somalia, as part of al-Shabaab's [[Ramadan]] offensive-attacking Somali TFG and [[AMISOM]] forces positions from the districts it controlled in the [[Mogadishu|city]] and the surrounding area.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/terrorists-wage-war-on-mogadishu|title=Terrorists Wage War on Mogadishu|publisher=Critical Threats|date=25 August 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/mogadishu-map-al-shabaabs-ramadan-offensive|title=Mogadishu Map: al Shabaab's Ramadan Offensive|publisher=Critical Threats|date=23 September 2010}}</ref> |- style="background:white" |December 20–23 |As a consequence of fighting with al-Shabaab weakening the group, Hizbul Islam's leader surrendered and the group merged into al-Shabaab.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.stanford.edu/group/mappingmilitants/cgi-bin/groups/view/113|title=Hizbul Islam|publisher=Stanford University|date=20 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.stanford.edu/group/mappingmilitants/cgi-bin/groups/view/61|title=Al Shabaab|publisher=Stanford University|date=20 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2010/12/23/us-somalia-conflict-idUSTRE6BM3AG20101223|publisher=Reuters|title=Somalia's Shabaab threatens Uganda, Burundi attacks|date=23 December 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201012201376.html|title=Somalia: Rival Militant Groups Set to Join Forces|publisher=allAfrica.com |date=20 December 2010 |accessdate=24 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201012210370.html|title=Somalia: Aweys Surrenders to Al Shabaab, Six Killed in Bombing|publisher=allafrica.com}}</ref> |}
== 2011 == [[File:Osama bin Laden hideout-en.svg|thumb|Diagram of [[Osama bin Laden's hideout compound|Osama bin Laden's hideout]] in [[Abbottabad]], he was [[Death of Osama bin Laden|killed]] there on 2 May 2011.]]
{| class="wikitable" |- ! Dates !! Events |- style="background:white" |Unknown |AQAP created [[Ansar al-Sharia (Yemen)|Ansar Al-Sharia (AAS (Yemen))]] as a Yemen-based affiliate focused on waging an insurgency rather than international attacks on the West<ref name=":02">{{Cite conference|last=International Crisis Group|title=Yemen's al-Qaeda: Expanding the Base|accessdate=2017-02-02|date=2017-02-02|url=https://www.crisisgroup.org/middle-east-north-africa/gulf-and-arabian-peninsula/yemen/174-yemen-s-al-qaeda-expanding-base}}</ref> the [[International Crisis Group]] said that AQAP is "an internally diverse organization with varying layers of support among the local population" and many AAS members and allies are not committed to AQAP's international agenda.<ref name=":02" /> |- style="background:khaki" |January–March 31 |Taking advantage of the [[Yemeni Revolution]], AQAP terrorists and AAS (Yemen) [[al-Qaeda insurgency in Yemen#Revolution (2011–2012)|takes over parts]] of [[Abyan Governorate]] (including [[Jaʿār]]) in Yemen, where on March 31 they reportedly declared the Governorate an "Al-Qaeda Emirate in Yemen" after seizing control of the region.<ref>Al Bawaba News [http://www.eurasiareview.com/yemen-al-qaeda-declares-south-province-as-islamic-emirate-31032011/ "Yemen: Al Qaeda Declares South province As “Islamic Emirate”"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110404011947/http://www.eurasiareview.com/yemen-al-qaeda-declares-south-province-as-islamic-emirate-31032011/ |date=4 April 2011 }} ''Eurasia Review'' 31 March 31, 2011</ref> ''The New York Times'' reported that those in control, while Islamic militants, are not in fact al-Qaeda.<ref>New York Times [https://www.nytimes.com/2011/05/31/world/middleeast/31yemen.html/ Islamist Seize a Yemeni City, Stoking Fears]</ref> |- style="background:orangered" |February 23 |'''[[Sinai insurgency|Islamist militants begin an insurgency]]''' in the [[Sinai Peninsula]]. |- style="background:lightgreen" |May 2 |[[Death of Osama bin Laden#Operation Neptune Spear|Operation Neptune Spear]] takes place: [[Osama bin Laden]] and 4 other terrorists are killed in a raid by U.S. Navy SEALs of [[United States Naval Special Warfare Development Group|DEVGRU]] on his residence in [[Abbottabad]], [[Pakistan]]. |- style="background:lightgreen" |May 22–23 |The [[PNS Mehran attack]] took place: 15 al-Qaeda and TTP terrorists attacked [[PNS Mehran]]-the headquarters of the [[Pakistan Navy]]'s [[Pakistan Naval Air Arm|Naval Air Arm]], resulting in 18 Pakistani servicemen killed and 16 more wounded, the terrorists lost 4 killed, 5 wounded and 4 captured. |- style="background:khaki" |May 27–September 10 |The [[Battle of Zinjibar]] takes place: 300 AQAP and AAS (Yemen) terrorists attacked and captured [[Zinjibar]] in Abyan Governorate, Yemen, and later the surrounding area. Fighting continued with Yemeni forces and armedtribesman (supported by the US) attempts to liberate the city being repelled in June and July; the terrorist force later rose up 2,000 fighters, they were joined by 400 members of al-Shabaab, terrorists from the [[Aden-Abyan Islamic Army]] and other militants also took part in the fighting. Ultimately Government forces were not able to retake the city and the terrorists entrenched themselves in the city; between 374-386 terrorists and militants killed and further 128 wounded and 12 captured, whilst Yemeni forces lost 232 killed, over 330 soldiers wounded, 50 soldiers missing and 10 captured, 51 tribesmen were also killed. |- style="background:lightgreen" |June 3 |A US drone strike in South Waziristan, Pakistan, kills [[Ilyas Kashmiri]], a senior al-Qaeda terrorist and leader of [[Harkat-ul-Jihad al-Islami|Harkat-ul-Jihad al-Islami (HuJI)]] and [[Lashkar al-Zil]], 8 other militants were also killed and 3 wounded. |- style="background:lightgreen" |July 20–21 |Delta Force, supported by US Army Rangers, Afghan SOF elements and US military air assets, attacked a foreign fighter staging area in southeast Paktika Province, Afghanistan, that was facilitated by the [[Haqqani Network]]. An estimated 80 to 100 Haqqani and foreign fighters were killed as was a Delta Force operator.<ref>Neville, Leigh, '' Special Forces in the War on Terror (General Military)'', Osprey Publishing, 2015 {{ISBN|978-1-4728-0790-8}}, p.274-275</ref> |- style="background:goldenrod" |August 6 |The Battle of Mogadishu (2010–11) ends following a final, two-week offensive by Somali TFG and AMISOM forces which forced the al-Shabaab terrorists to withdraw from the capital to its strongholds in the central and southern part of Somalia; though small pockets remained until October 10.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/aug/07/somali-troops-mogadishu-rebels-out|title=Somali troops move to secure Mogadishu as rebels pull out|publisher=the Guardian|date=7 August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/al-shabaabs-withdrawal-from-mogadishu|title=Al Shabaab's Withdrawal from Mogadishu|publisher=Critical Threats|date=7 August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-15246093|title=Somalia Islamists al-Shabab 'driven out of Mogadishu'|publisher=BBC|date=10 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/commoditiesNews/idAFL6E7J601H20110806?pageNumber=1&virtualBrandChannel=0|title=UPDATE 3-Somali government declares Islamist rebellion defeated|publisher=Reuters|date=6 August 2011}}</ref> |- style="background:white" |October |The [[Movement for Oneness and Jihad in West Africa|Movement for Oneness and Jihad in West Africa (MOJWA)]] broke with AQIM, with the alleged goal of spreading its ideology further into areas of West Africa that were not within the scope of AQIM. Some analysts believe that the split of the Black African-led MOJWA is a consequence of the Algerian predominance on AQIM's leadership. |- style="background:goldenrod" |October 16 |[[Operation Linda Nchi]] began: After a series of cross-border raids (including kidnappings of mostly foreigners workers and tourists) by al-Shabaab terrorists, Kenyan forces invade Somalia to secure its borders and combat al-Shabaab in the country.<ref name="Somalia profile - Timeline"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-15331448|title=Kenya sends troops into Somalia to hit al-Shabab|publisher=BBC|date=17 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/opinion/2011/11/201111181332359678.html|title=Kenya's blundering mission in Somalia|publisher=Al Jazeera|date=2 November 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foreignaffairs.com/articles/africa/2011-11-15/why-kenya-invaded-somalia|title=Why Kenya Invaded Somalia|publisher=Foreign Affairs|date=15 November 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-15337464|title=Kenya's incursion into Somalia raises the stakes|publisher=BBC|date=17 October 2011}}</ref> |- style="background:khaki" |December 18 |U.S. military forces withdraw from Iraq, ending the '''[[Iraq War]]'''. |}
== 2012 == [[File:Ansar Dine Rebels - VOA.jpg|thumb|[[Ansar Dine]] terrorists during the offensive against the Mali government, 2012]] {| class="wikitable" |- ! Dates !! Events |- style="background:forestgreen" |January 16 |The '''[[Northern Mali conflict]]''' begins when Islamic insurgents (affiliated with al-Qaeda) and a [[National Movement for the Liberation of Azawad|nationalist rebel group]] launch an offensive against the Mali government. |- style="background:white" |February 9 |Al-Shabaab formally becomes part of al-Qaeda.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-16979440|title=Somalia's al-Shabab join al-Qaeda|publisher=BBC|date=10 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2012/02/shabaab_formally_joi.php|title=Shabaab formally joins al Qaeda|publisher=Long War Journal|date=9 February 2012}}</ref> |- style="background:khaki" |March 4–5 |The [[Battle of Dofas]] takes place in Abyan Governorate in Yemen: AQAP and AAS (Yemen) terrorists successfully attacked Yemeni forces in the small town of Dofas on the outskirts of Zinjibar, destroying a Yemeni Army artillery battalion and capturing large quantities of weapons, including heavy ones, among them tanks. 42 terrorists and militants were killed, whilst Yemeni forces lost 187 killed, 135 wounded and 55-73 captured. |- style="background:forestgreen" |March 8 |The [[Sokoto hostage rescue attempt]] takes place: Operators from the British Special Boat Service and Nigerian army soldiers attempted to rescue a British and Italian hostage in [[Sokoto]], [[Nigeria]], who were being held by members of [[Boko Haram]] who were backed by al-Qaeda, calling themselves "al-Qaida in the land beyond the Sahil". The rescue mission failed, both hostages were murdered by their captors, however 8 of them were killed and 2-3 arrested. |- style="background:goldenrod" |March 8–July 6 |Operation Linda Nchi ends after Kenyan forces in Somalia integrated into AMISOM (a process that was agreed in February with the [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 2036|UN Security Council Resolution 2036]] which then began in March and was formally completed by July 6) having weakened al-Shabaab by killing at least 700 to at least roughly 920 terrorists and liberating most areas (including key areas) under their control; Kenyan Somali TFG and other forces in Somalia lost 21–72 killed, 152 injured.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.criticalthreats.org/analysis/timeline-operation-linda-nchi#MonthOne|title=Timeline: Operation Linda Nchi|publisher=Critical Threats|date=24 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://amisom-au.org/kenya-kdf/|title=Kenya – KDF|publisher=AMISOM}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201203200023.html|title=Kenya: Operation Linda Nchi Ends As African Union Takes Over|publisher=allafrica.com|date=18 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nation.co.ke/News/KDF+We+have+killed+700+militants+/-/1056/1301746/-/15c3vh4z/-/index.html|title=KDF: We have killed 700 militants|publisher=Daily Nation|date=7 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://amisom-au.org/2012/07/amisom-assumes-formal-command-of-kenyan-forces-in-somalia/|title=AMISOM ASSUMES FORMAL COMMAND OF KENYAN FORCES IN SOMALIA|publisher=AMISOM}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-18288639|title=Somalia forces capture key al-Shabab town of Afmadow|publisher=BBC|date=31 May 2012}}</ref> |- style="background:lightgreen" |April 29 |A US drone strike in [[Miramshah]], North Waziristan, Pakistan, killed Abu Usman Adil, the leader of the IMU, and 3 other terrorists.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2012/08/imu_announces_death_1.php|title=IMU announces death of emir, names new leader|accessdate=4 August 2012}}</ref> |- style="background:khaki" |May 12 – June 15 |The [[2012 Abyan offensive]] takes place: Yemeni forces successfully carry out a major offensive to retake the parts of Abyan Governorate under terrorist and militant occupation; by mid-June, government forces recapture Zinjibar, Jaʿār and other areas in mid-June, forcing the terrorists and militants to pull back to Azzan in [[Shabwah Governorate]], whom abandoned it on June 17, forcing AQAP and other terrorists and militants return to an insurgency campaign in Abyan and neighboring provinces. |- style="background:white" |Summer |The terrorist group [[Jaish al-Muhajireen wal-Ansar|Katibat al-Muhajireen (Muhajireen Brigade) is established-it was later renamed Jaish al-Muhajireen wal-Ansar (JMA)]], with an oath of allegiance to the Caucuses Emirate, it was led by [[Abu Omar al-Shishani]] (alternatively called Tarkhan Batirashvili). |- style="background:orangered" |September 11 |The [[2012 Benghazi attack|Benghazi attack]] by [[Ansar al-Sharia (Libya)|Ansar al-Sharia in Libya (ASL)]] and other Islamist militants kills 4 and injures 7. |- style="background:goldenrod" |September 28–October 1 |The [[Battle of Kismayo (2012)|Second Battle of Kismayo]] took place in Somalia: AMISOM and Somali TFG forces, allegedly with the [[Raskamboni Movement]], launched Operation Sledge Hammer, which forced al-Shabaab to withdraw from the port, the terrorists had been using the area as an operational and financial hub.<ref name="Al Shabaab After Kismayo"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.stanford.edu/group/mappingmilitants/cgi-bin/groups/view/489?highlight=kismayo+2008|title=Ras Kamboni Movement|publisher=Stanford University|date=12 January 2016}}</ref> |}
== 2013 == [[File:Soldats français à Gao.PNG|thumb|French soldiers on patrol in [[Gao]], spring 2013.]] [[File:ISIL car bomb explodes in Menagh Air Base.gif|thumb|[[Jaish al-Muhajireen wal-Ansar|JMA]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/08/06/world/middleeast/rebels-gain-control-of-government-air-base-in-syria.html?_r=0|title=Rebels Gain Control of Government Air Base in Syria |publisher= The Telegraph |date= 5 August 2013}}</ref> or an [[ISIL]] [[suicide attack|suicide bomber]] detonates a [[car bomb]] during the [[Siege of Menagh Air Base|final assault on the Menagh Air Base]]. 5 August 2013.]] {| class="wikitable" |- ! Dates !! Events |- style="background:goldenrod" |January 11 |The [[Bulo Marer hostage rescue attempt]] takes place: Operators from the [[Directorate-General for External Security|DGSE]] attempted to rescue 2 French hostages [[Bulo Marer]], Somalia being held by [[Al-Shabaab (militant group)|al-Shabaab]], the rescue mission failed, 2 DGSE operators were killed as was the hostage, 17 al-Shabaab terrorists were killed. |- style="background:forestgreen" |January 13 |The [[French Military]], supported by several [[Economic Community of West African States|African nations]] [[Operation Serval|intervene]] in the Northern Mali Conflict, supporting Mali security forces against [[Movement for Oneness and Jihad in West Africa|Movement for Oneness and Jihad in West Africa (MOJWA)]], [[Al-Qaeda in Islamic Maghreb|Al-Qaeda in Islamic Maghreb (AQIM)]] and [[Ansar Dine]]. |- style="background:orangered" |January 16 |The [[In Amenas hostage crisis]] in Algeria begins, ending on January 19, which kills 40 hostages. The terrorists responsible were affiliated with [[Al-Mourabitoun (militant group)|al-Mourabitoun]]. |- style="background:white" |April |ISI (Islamic State of Iraq) changes its name to [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant (ISIL)]] after expanding into Syria; throughout the month it made rapid military gains in northern Syria, in admits the '''[[Syrian Civil War]]'''. |- style="background:khaki" |May 11 |The [[Reyhanlı bombings]] in Turkey kill 52 and injure 140. |- style="background:khaki" |August 4–19 |[[2013 Latakia offensive]] takes place: [[Free Syrian Army]] rebels, fighting separately with [[al-Nusra Front]], ISIL and JMA terrorists, along with militants from the [[Syrian Islamic Front]]'s [[Ahrar al-Sham]], jihadists from the [[Suqour al-Ezz]] and Harakat Sham al Islam (designated a terrorist group in September 2014), attempted an offensive to takeover parts of [[Latakia Governorate]] in Syria from pro-Syrian government forces. The anti-government force initially seized over a dozen villages, but a counter offensive by pro-Syrian government forces retook most of the governorate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2013/08/201382810616786551.html|title= Inside the battle for Assad's heartland|publisher=Al-Jazeeradate=23 August 2013}}</ref><ref name="longwarjournal.org">{{cite web|url=http://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2014/04/former_guantanamo_de_2.php|title=Former Guantanamo detainee killed while leading jihadist group in Syria|publisher=|accessdate=24 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2014/09/us_adds_chechen_moro.php|title=State Department adds Chechen, Moroccan-led jihadist groups to terrorist list|publisher=Long War Journal|date=24 September 2014}}</ref> At least 107 rebels, militants, jihadists and terrorists were killed whilst 114 to 127 pro-Syrian government soldiers and 44 militiamen killed. |- style="background:khaki" |August 5/6 |ISIL and JMA terrorists, along with militants from the Syrian Islamic Front's Ahrar al-Sham, militants from the [[Syrian Islamic Liberation Front]]'s [[Al-Tawhid Brigade]], and the Free Syrian Army's [[Northern Storm Brigade]] as well as 4 other groups seized the Syrian Pro-government held [[Menagh Military Airbase]] in [[Aleppo Governorate]] Syria, ending the year long [[Siege of Menagh Air Base|siege of the airbase]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/syria/10228171/Syria-Foreign-jihadists-behind-the-rebel-capture-of-Aleppo-airport.html|title=Syria: Foreign jihadists behind the rebel capture of Aleppo airport|publisher=The Telegraph|date=7 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2013/08/06/world/meast/syria-civil-war/index.html|title=Opposition group: Syrian rebels, foreigners take over regime air base|publisher=CNN|date=6 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-syria-crisis-airport/syrian-rebels-capture-military-airport-near-turkey-idUSBRE97411J20130805|title=Syrian rebels capture military airport near Turkey|publisher=Reuters|date=5 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/08/06/world/middleeast/rebels-gain-control-of-government-air-base-in-syria.html?_r=0|title=Rebels Gain Control of Government Air Base in Syria|publisher=The Telegraph|date=5 August 2013}}</ref> |- style="background:white" |August 30 |MOJWA and [[Al-Mulathameen]] merged to form [[Al-Mourabitoun]].<ref name="Long War Journal">{{cite web|url=https://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2016/10/islamic-state-recognizes-oath-of-allegiance-from-jihadists-in-west-africa.php|title=Islamic State recognizes oath of allegiance from jihadists in Mali|publisher=Long War Journal|date=31 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.un.org/sc/suborg/en/sanctions/1267/aq_sanctions_list/summaries/entity/al-mourabitoun|title=QDe.141AL MOURABITOUN|publisher=UN.org|date=2 June 2014}}</ref> |- style="background:goldenrod" |September 21–24 |The [[Westgate shopping mall attack]] in [[Nairobi]], [[Kenya]], carried out by al-Shabaab, kills 67 and injures 175. |- style="background:lightgreen" |November 1 |A U.S. drone strike in the village of [[Dande Darpakhel]] in North Waziristan, Pakistan, killed [[Hakimullah Mehsud]], the leader of the TTP. |- style="background:white" |late November-early December |Abu Omar al-Shishani, the leader of the JMA, swore his allegiance to [[Abu Bakr al-Baghdadi]], the leader of the ISIL, causing the terrorist group to split, with hundreds of its members siding with Abu Omar al-Shishani and joining ISIL. Salahuddin al-Shishani was appointed the new commander of the JMA with the terrorists who were still loyal to the Caucuses Emirate. |- style="background:khaki" |December 30 |ISIL and its allied insurgent groups and militias began what was known as the [[Anbar campaign (2013–14)|Anbar campaign]] to take over large parts of al Anbar Governorate in Iraq. |}
== 2014 ==
[[File:İD bayrağı ile bir militan.jpg|thumb|ISIL terrorist carrying the group's flag on a hill overlooking the town of [[Dabiq, Syria|Dabiq]] in Syria, 2014.]] [[File:Airstrikes in Syria 140923-F-UL677-654.jpg|thumb|Two U.S. [[McDonnell Douglas F-15E Strike Eagle|F-15E]]'s flying over Iraq after conducting airstrikes in Syria, 23 September 2014.]] [[File:2014 10 06 Capture Of Barawe-18.jpg (15457584912).jpg|thumb|[[Uganda People's Defence Force|Ugandan special forces]] members clearing buildings in [[Barawe]] in Somalia as part of [[Operation Indian Ocean]], 6 October 2014.]] [[File:North waziristan clearence.jpg|thumb|Pakistani forces clear the village of Mirali in [[North Waziristan]], Pakistan, as part of [[Operation Zarb-e-Azb]]]] [[File:USS Carl Vinson (CVN 70) 141109-N-OO356-079 (15725449028).jpg|thumb|The [[USS Carl Vinson]], escorted by [[HMS Defender (D36)|HMS Defender]], [[USS Bunker Hill (CG-52)|USS Bunker Hill]] and [[French frigate Jean Bart|FS Jean Bart]] in the [[Persian Gulf]] for strike operations in Iraq and Syria. 10 November 2014.]] [[File:Coalition Airstrike on ISIL position in Kobane.jpg|thumb|Coalition Airstrikes on ISIL positions in [[Kobanî]] in Syria, during the [[Siege of Kobanî|battle for the city]], 19 November 2014.]] {| class="wikitable" |- ! Dates !! Events |- style="background:white" |January |The Suqour al-Ezz group joined al-Nusra Front.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtoninstitute.org/policy-analysis/view/inside-baseball-on-syrian-rebel-infighting|title=Inside Baseball on Syrian Rebel Infighting|publisher=The Wshington institute.org|date=7 February 2014}}</ref> |- style="background:white" |February |Al-Qaeda formally dissociated itself and broke off links with its former affiliate ISIL, leaving the al-Nusra Front the main representative of al-Qaeda in Syria. |- style="background:goldenrod" |February or March-before August |AMISOM and the [[Somali Armed Forces]] carry out Operation Eagle in South Central Somalia: the offensive resulted in 11 significant towns being liberated in the regions of [[Bay, Somalia|Bay]], [[Bakool]], [[Gedo]], [[Lower Shebelle]], [[Middle Shebelle]], [[Galguduud]] and [[Hiran, Somalia|Hiran]].<ref name="AMISOM">{{cite web|url=http://amisom-au.org/2014/10/joint-security-update-on-operation-indian-ocean-by-somali-government-and-amisom/|title=Joint security update on Operation Indian Ocean by Somali Government and AMISOM|publisher=AMISOM}}</ref><ref name="UNHCR">{{cite web |url= https://data2.unhcr.org/ar/documents/download/31953 |title= UPDATE {{!}} Displacements caused by military offensive in South-Central Somalia |publisher= UNHCR |date= September 2014}}</ref><ref name="G. Jones, Seth 2016">G. Jones, Seth, Liepman, Andrew M., Chandler, Nathan, ''Counterterrorism and Counterinsurgency in Somalia: Assessing the Campaign Against Al Shabaab'', RAND, 2016, {{ASIN|B01N4G4OY1}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.defenceweb.co.za/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=47928:rebuilding-the-somali-army&catid=49:National%20Security&Itemid=115|title=Rebuilding the Somali army|publisher=defence web|date=23 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.france24.com/en/20140516-operation-eagle-somalia-fight-against-al-shabaab-african-union-al-qaeda|title=In photos: Tracking al Shabaab in Somalia|publisher=France 24|date=19 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.strategypage.com/qnd/somalia/20140519.aspx|title=Somalia: Operation Eagle Chases Ghosts|publisher=Strategy Page}}</ref> |- style="background:khaki" |Mid-March |The [[Shabwah Governorate offensive (2014–present)]] by AQAP terrorists to take control of Shabwah Governorate in Yemen begins. |- style="background:khaki" |March 21–June 15 |The [[2014 Latakia offensive|Latakia offensive (2014)]] takes place in Latakia Governorate, Syria: al-Nusra Front, JMA and Harakat Sham al-Islam terrorists, along with militants from the [[Islamic Front (Syria)]]'s Ahrar al-Sham and [[Ansar al-Sham]] (with the alleged backing of Turkey) launched the offensive with the aim of taking over of all strategic observatories, government villages and the Mediterranean coast and/or force the Syrian army to redeploy forces to Latakia Governorate, which would relieve pressure on other rebels elsewhere in Syria. The terrorists and militants seized [[Kessab]] and other strategic areas which pro-government Syrian forces and other allied militias diverted to Latakia from Idlib, Hama Governorate and the [[Battle of Aleppo (2012–2016)|Battle of Aleppo]] to launch a counteroffensive. With the support of Hezbollah terrorists, Iraqi Shia militia, Iranian military advisers, pro-Government forces eventually recaptured all territory previously lost to the terrorists and militants and stall any further advances. Between 582 and 2,700 Terrorists, militants and rebels were killed as well as 5,635 wounded, [[Ibrahim Bin Shakaran]], the leader of Harakat Sham al-Islam, was killed during the offensive; between 50 and 571 pro-Government forces were killed. US-backed Free Syrian Army rebels, with Turkish military support, were reportedly involved in the offensive.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2014/09/us_adds_chechen_moro.php|title=State Department adds Chechen, Moroccan-led jihadist groups to terrorist list|publisher=The Long War Journal|date=24 September 2014}}</ref><ref name="longwarjournal.org"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.stanford.edu/group/mappingmilitants/cgi-bin/groups/view/531|title=Ansar al-Sham|publisher=Stanford University|date=17 February 2017}}</ref> |- style="background:khaki" |April 10–July 14 |Taking advantage of the [[Deir ez-Zor clashes (2011–14)]] between Syrian forces loyal to [[Bashar al-Assad]] and the [[Free Syrian Army]] ([[National Coalition for Syrian Revolutionary and Opposition Forces|SNC]]-aligned units) in [[Deir ez-Zor Governorate]] in Syria; ISIL terrorists launched the [[Deir ez-Zor offensive (April–July 2014)]] which by 14 July defeated the Free Syrian Army and other rebel units, as well as al-Nusra; and captured almost the whole province, except a part of the provincial capital, the military airport on its southern outskirts and a few of the surrounding towns, which were garrisoned by pro-Assad forces. At least 267 ISIL terrorists were killed as were 414 rebels and terrorists were killed, the end of the offensive marked the beginning of the [[Siege of Deir ez-Zor (2014–17)|Siege of Deir ez-Zor]]. |- style="background:white" |June 3 |[[Transit Center at Manas|Operation Enduring Freedom – Kyrgyzstan]] ends. |- style="background:khaki" |June 4–29 |ISIL terrorists, Iraqi Ba'ath Party loyalists and other militants carried out their [[Northern Iraq offensive (June 2014)|Northern Iraq offensive]], capturing most of Saladin and Nineveh Governorate (including [[Fall of Mosul|Capturing Mosul]]) and parts of Kirkuk Governorate, and Diyala Governorate, Iraqi government and Kurdish counterattacks managed to regain some of the territory lost. Iraqi government and Kurdish forces lost over 800 killed, 1,900 missing (1,566 executed in the [[Camp Speicher massacre]]) and 90,000 deserted whilst ISIL and anti-government militants lost over 711 militants and terrorists. By June 23, ISIL and its allied militants taking part in their Anbar campaign captured of at least 70% of Al Anbar Governorate, suffering 2,055 killed and 528 captured, whilst Iraqi government forces lost between 300–6,000 killed and 12,000 deserted; they were halted by Iraqi security forces on June 25 before they reached the Haditha Dam. On June 29, ISIL proclaimed itself and its territory as a caliphate with Abu Bakr al-Baghdadi named as its [[caliph]] and the terrorist group formally called itself Islamic State. By this time, ISIL had largely defeated its rivals and former allies, with many who had not been killed or driven away pledging allegiance to the terrorist group. |- style="background:khaki" |June 13 |'''[[Military intervention against the Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|International campaign against ISIL]]''' begins with the [[American-led intervention in Iraq]] against ISIL. |- style="background:lightgreen" |June 15 |The Pakistani military began [[Operation Zarb-e-Azb]]: A military offensive to "flush out" all foreign and local militants hiding in North Waziristan in Pakistan, including the TTP, IMU, ETIM, LeJ, al-Qaeda, [[Jundallah (Pakistan)|Jundallah]] and the Haqqani network. |- style="background:khaki" |June 30 |The [[First Battle of Tikrit]] ends after ISIL terrorists, Ba'athists and Sunni militants (that soon become part of the group), seized the city in Saladin Governorate, Iraq, from Iraqi government forces' control, whom were supported by the US forces, the battle had begun on June 26 as part of [[Salahuddin campaign]] (that had begun on 5 June as part of ISIS' Northern Iraq offensive). Between 25 and over 215 terrorists and militants were killed, over 35 Iraqi government forces were killed. |- style="background:khaki" |July 4 |Operators from Delta force [[2014 American rescue mission in Syria|attempted to rescue]] two dozen hostages who was being held by ISIL in Syria, but it was discovered that the hostages had been moved 24 hours before, at least 5 ISIL terrorists were killed during the mission. |- style="background:forestgreen" |July 15 |[[Operation Serval]]: the French and African intervention in the Northern Mali conflict ends, the operation killed Between 600–1,000 terrorists and captured 109–300 more. |- style="background:khaki" |July 23–August 28 |ISIL carries out its [[2014 Eastern Syria offensive|Eastern Syria offensive]], the terrorists took over all of Raqqa Governorate following the conclusion of the [[Battle of Al-Tabqa airbase]]-the last pro-Syrian government stronghold in the Governorate. Pro-Syrian government forces and [[Rojava]]'s [[People's Protection Units|YPG]] managed to stop ISIL from taking over most of [[Al-Hasakah Governorate]], and gaining anymore territory in Aleppo Governorate. Between 456 and over 586 ISIL terrorists were killed, pro-Syrian Government forces and the YPG lost at least 549 killed, 32 missing and 10 captured. |- style="background:white" |July 23 |ASG leader, [[Isnilon Hapilon]], swore the groups allegiance to ISIL. |- style="background:white" |July 25 |The JMA and the terrorist/jihadist groups Harakat Sham al-Islam, Harakat Fajr ash-Sham al-Islamiya and the [[Green Battalion]] formed an alliance called [[Ansar al-Din Front]]. |- style="background:darksalmon" |August 1 |[[Operation Barkhane]] began: French and African forces began anti-insurgent operation in Africa's [[Sahel]] region, particularly against al-Mourabitoun, AQIM and Ansar Dine. |- style="background:khaki" |August 1–19 |ISIL carries out [[Northern Iraq offensive (August 2014)|another offensive in northern Iraq]], capturing [[Battle of Zumar|Zummar]] [[Sinjar]] and the [[Mosul Dam]], however Kurdish and Iraqi government, supported by US, UK and Australian forces, break ISIL's siege of [[Sinjar Mountains|Mount Sinjar]] and evacuate the majority of 50,000 [[Yazidis]] trapped on Mount Sinjar by August 13. Iraqi government forces and Kurdish forces supported by US military assets [[Battle for Mosul Dam|retook the dam after 4 days of fighting]]. At least 100 ISIL terrorists were killed and a further 160 wounded and 38 captured. |- style="background:goldenrod" |August 8–October 17 |The [[Galgala campaign]] takes place: The [[Puntland Dervish Force]] and the [[Puntland Intelligence Agency]] launched the campaign to re-gain control of the Galgala hills in the [[Galgala]] area of [[Puntland]] in Somalia from al-Shabaab control, the terrorists were reportedly aided by soldiers from the [[List of states with limited recognition|self-declared state]] of [[Somaliland]]. The final al-Shabaab stronghold fell on October 17, bringing the campaign to a successful conclusion and al-Shabaab went back to being a low-level insurgency in area; at least 96 terrorists and Somaliland soldiers were killed, Puntland lost at least 18 killed and 40 wounded. |- style="background:goldenrod" |August 25 or 29–October 31 |[[Operation Indian Ocean]] takes place: AMISOM and the Somali Armed Forces removed al-Shabaab from its remaining coastal strongholds in South Central Somalia; there were at least 8 in total, which included [[Barawe]] (which was a significant loss for the terrorist group, whom had used the port as its main safe haven and was an important source of revenue), [[Bulo Marer]] and [[Adale]]. The operation was also aimed at clearing any remaining terrorists from the countryside, the force liberated [[Jalalaqsi]]-the last al-Shabaab stonghold in the Hiran region. The force captured at least 700 al-Shabaab terrorists.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.securitycouncilreport.org/atf/cf/%7B65BFCF9B-6D27-4E9C-8CD3-CF6E4FF96FF9%7D/S_2015_51.pdf|title=United Nations Security Council report|date=23 January 2015}}</ref><ref>Oloya, Opiyo, ''Black Hawks Rising: The Story of AMISOM's Successful War against Somali Insurgents, 2007-2014'', Helion and Company, 2016, {{ISBN|1910777692}} {{ISBN|978-1910777695}}</ref><ref name=UNHCR/><ref name="G. Jones, Seth 2016"/><ref>Osudibia, Kizito Chike, ''Religion and the Global Resurgence of Violence: : Connection of the Abrahamics'', AuthorHouse, 2016, {{ISBN|1524642509}} {{ISBN|978-1524642501}}</ref><ref name="AMISOM"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://amisom-au.org/2016/07/somalia-on-the-path-to-peace-and-stability/|title=Somalia: On The Path To Peace and Stability|publisher=AMISOM}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://goobjoog.com/english/at-least-700-al-shabab-members-surrenders-to-the-governmentpm-abdiweli/|title=At least 700 Al-shabab members surrenders to the government, PM Abdiweli|publisher=Goobjoog News|date=11 October 2014}}</ref> |- style="background:khaki" |August 31 |The [[Siege of Amirli]] ended in Saladin Governorate, Iraqi government and militias, the Kurdish peshmerga and Iranian forces, supported by the coalition, broke ISIL' siege of the [[Amirli|town]] that had begun on June 11 as part of the Salahuddin campaign. At least 147 ISIS terrorists and Ba'athist militants were killed and 15 captured, whilst the combined force lost at least 16 killed and 39 wounded. |- style="background:goldenrod" |September 1 |A U.S. drone strike in southern Somalia killed [[Ahmed Abdi Godane]], the leader of al-Shabaab, along with 6 other terrorists. |- style="background:khaki" |September 15 |The [[Siege of Kobanî]] begins: ISIL began a massive offensive towards to capture the [[Kobanî Canton]], (particularly the city of [[Kobanî]]) in Aleppo Governorate, Syria. By October, ISIL had taken most of the Canton and the city. |- style="background:khaki" |September 22 |The international campaign against ISIL continues with the [[American-led intervention in Syria]]. |- style="background:white" |Early October |As part of the Ansar al-Din Front, the Green Battalion merges with the JMA. |- style="background:lightgreen" |October |Pakistani military began [[Operation Khyber]] against terrorists and Islamist insurgents in the [[Khyber Agency]] of Pakistan, the operation of four phases. |- style="background:khaki" |October 29–December 21 |The [[Battle of Baiji (2014)|Second Battle of Baiji]] takes place as part of the Salahuddin campaign: After the [[Fall of Baiji]] in Saladin Governorate to ISIL during their Northern Iraq offensive in June, Iraqi forces, Hezbollah terrorists, Iranian forces, supported by the coalition, retook [[Baiji, Iraq|the city]] and broke the siege at the oil refinery in November, but ISIL launched a counterattack in December and recaptured the city and re-established a siege of the oil refinery. Over 100 terrorists were killed; and over 500 of the combined force were killed. |- style="background:white" |November 10–13 |Members of [[Ansar Bait al-Maqdis|Ansar Bait al-Maqdis (ABM)]] began swearing an oath of allegiance to Abu Bakr al-Baghdadi, thus merging with ISIL and becoming the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant – Sinai Province|Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant – Sinai Province (ISIL-SP).]] |- style="background:white" |November 13 |ISIL announced that [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant – Yemen Province|Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant – Yemen Province (ISIL-YP)]] had been established in Yemen. |- style="background:khaki" |November 21 |The [[Battle of Ramadi (2014–15)]] begins: ISIL terrorists attacked the city, which was one of the Iraqi government's last strongholds in Al Anbar Governorate, Iraq. |- style="background:khaki" |November 26–December 6 |U.S. Navy SEALs and Yemen special forces soldiers carried out [[2014 hostage rescue operations in Yemen|missions to rescue hostages]] being held by AQAP in Yemen: On the first raid in [[Hadhramaut Governorate]] – 8 hostages were rescued and 7 AQAP terrorists were killed. On the second raid in Shabwah Governorate: a firefight ensued 6 AQAP terrorists were killed, 2 hostages were mortally wounded and later died. |- style="background:lightgreen" |December 16 |TTP terrorists carried out the [[2014 Peshawar school massacre|Peshawar school massacre]] in Pakistan, which killed 149 and injured 114 people. |- style="background:khaki" |December 23 |The [[Battle of Baiji (2014–15)|Third Battle of Baiji]] begins: As part of the Salahuddin campaign, Iraqi and Iranian forces, with Shia militia, supported by the coalition, begin the battle to retake the city after the ISIL counterattack that seized the city 2 days before. |- style="background:lightgreen" |December 28 |NATO officially ended combat operations in Afghanistan<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/america-formally-ends-the-war-in-afghanistan|title=U.S. formally ends the war in Afghanistan|publisher=CBA News|date=28 December 2014}}</ref> ending the War in Afghanistan (2001-2014) phase of the war. |- style="background:khaki" |December 28–30 |The [[Dhuluiya offensive]] by Iraqi government forces and Shia militia, as well as local Sunni tribesman liberated [[Dhuluiya]] in Saladin Governorate, Iraq, from ISIL and broke their siege of the [[Jubur|Juburi tribe]] in the southern part of the town, as part of the Salahuddin campaign. The combined force lost 73 killed whilst terrorists lost 300 killed. |}
