bil Governorate and Nineveh Governorate, Iraqi government, Kurdish, coalition and Iranian forces, as well as Hezbollah terrorists and Ba'athists militants to liberate the city from ISIL occupation. |- style="background:goldenrod" |October 26–December 18 |The [[Qandala campaign]] takes place in Somalia, when ISS terrorists seized the weakly defended [[Qandala|port town]] in [[Bari, Somalia|Bari region]]. On December 3, the Puntland Security Force began a counter-offensive which cleared the town on December 7, as well as destroying an ISS base at a village 30&nbsp;km south of Qandala, where the terrorists were regrouping. 30 ISS terrorists were reportedly killed and a further 35 wounded, as well as several captured.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2017/02/islamic-state-claims-hotel-attack-in-northern-somalia.php|title=Islamic State claims hotel attack in northern Somalia|author=Caleb Weiss|publisher=[[Long War Journal]]|date=9 February 2017|accessdate=15 December 2017}}</ref> |- style="background:white" |October 30/31 |ISIL accepted a pledge of allegiance by [[Adnan Abu Walid al-Sahrawi]] and his followers, creating the Islamic State in Greater Sahara (ISGS).<ref name="Long War Journal"/> |- style="background:white" |October–November |Operation Active Endeavour ends following the [[2016 Warsaw summit]], where NATO leaders agreed to transition the operation to a non-Article 5 maritime security operation over a broader area of the Mediterranean, codenamed: [[Operation Sea Guardian]]. |- style="background:khaki" |November 6 |The Raqqa campaign (2016–2017) in Syria began: Syrian Democratic Forces, supported by coalition forces, launched the offensive to liberate Raqqa Governorate from ISIL occupation with the particular goal of isolating and eventually capturing the ISIL de facto capital Raqqa. |-style="background:cornflowerblue" | December 3 |The leader of ISIL-CP, [[Rustam Asildarov]], was killed in an FSB counterterrorism raid near [[Makhachkala]] in Dagestan, Russia, along with 4 other terrorists. |-style="background:cornflowerblue" | December 19 |An ISIL terrorist carried out the [[2016 Berlin attack|Berlin attack]] in Germany, killing 12 and injured 56 people. |- style="background:lightgreen" | December 31 | United States troops [[Withdrawal of U.S. troops from Afghanistan|withdraw]] from Afghanistan, leaving behind 8,400 troops stationed at 4 garrisons (Kabul, Kandahar, Bagram, and Jalalabad). |}
== 2017 == [[File:DOD 104006261-512x288-442k ISIL Training Camp near.ogv|thumb|US surveillance footage of one of the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant in Libya|ISIL in Libya]] camps near [[Sirte]], before it was destroyed in airstrikes on 18 January 2017.]] [[File:Marawi crisis troops 2.jpg|thumb|Filipino soldiers being deployed to participate in the [[Battle of Marawi]] in the Philippines, 5 June 2017.]] [[File:US fire support for SDF at Raqqa.png|thumb|U.S. Marine Corps artillery providing [[fire support]] to the Syrian Democratic Forces during the [[Battle of Raqqa (2017)]], 21 June 2017.]] [[File:Russian submarines firing missiles against ISIS.jpg|thumb|Russian submarines firing cruise missiles against ISIL in [[Deir ez-Zor]], Syria,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/russia-submarines-fire-cruise-missiles-isis-militants-fighters-syria-deir-ezzor-a7946491.html|title=Russian submarines fire seven cruise missiles at Isis militants|publisher=the Independent|date=14 September 2017}}</ref> during the [[Deir ez-Zor offensive (September 2017–present)]] as part of the [[Eastern Syria campaign (September–December 2017)]]. 14 September 2017.]] {| class="wikitable" |- ! Dates !! Events |- style="background:khaki" |January 1 |The [[2017 Istanbul nightclub attack|Istanbul nightclub attack]] in Turkey killed 39 and injured 70 people, ISIS claimed credit for the attack. |- style="background:orangered" |January 18 |Two USAF [[Northrop Grumman B-2 Spirit|B-2]] bombers dropped around 100 bombs on two ISIS camps 28 miles south of Sirte in Libya, killing 90 terrorists. A U.S. defense official said that "This was the largest remaining ISIS presence in Libya" and that "They have been largely marginalized but I am hesitant to say they've been completely eliminated in Libya." |- style="background:lightgrey" | January 27 |President [[Donald Trump]] signed Executive Order 13769, entitled [[Executive Order 13769|Protecting the Nation from Foreign Terrorist Entry into the United States]] to restrict immigration from several countries in the Middle East and North Africa. The order suspends the Syrian Refugee admissions for 120 days as well as immigration from Libya, Iran, Iraq, Somalia, Sudan, Syria and Yemen, regardless of visa status or permanent residency, for 90 days, with exceptions on a case-by-case basis. The order was met by criticism and lawsuit from [[American Civil Liberties Union]] as well as protests. |- style="background:white" |January 28 |The JFS became [[Tahrir al-Sham|Hayat Tahrir al-Sham (HTS)]] after they merged with Islamist and/or jihadists groups [[Nour al-Din al-Zenki Movement]], Ansar al-Din Front, [[Jaysh al-Sunna]] and [[Liwa al-Haqq (Idlib)|Liwa al-Haqq]]. |- style="background:lightgreen" |February 13 |The [[February 2017 Lahore suicide bombing|Lahore suicide bombing]] in Pakistan, carried out by members of [[Jamaat-ul-Ahrar|Jamaat-ul-Ahrar (JuA)]], kills 17 and injures over 90 people. |- style="background:lightgreen" |February 16 |The [[2017 Sehwan suicide bombing|Sehwan suicide bombing]] in Pakistan, carried out by members of ISIL-KP, killed over 88 and injured 350. |- style="background:lightgreen" |February 22 |In response to the recent terrorist attacks across Pakistan, the Pakistani military began [[Operation Radd-ul-Fasaad]]: The operation is aimed at indiscriminately eliminating the residual threat of terrorism and consolidating the gains of previous operations. |- style="background:white" |March 2 |The Sahara branch of AQIM merged with Ansar Dine and Al-Mourabitoun into [[Jama'at Nasr al-Islam wal Muslimin|Jama'at Nasr al-Islam wal Muslimin (JNIM)]]. |-style="background:cornflowerblue" |April 3 |The [[2017 Saint Petersburg Metro bombing|Saint Petersburg Metro bombing]] by a terrorist from the [[Imam Shamil Battalion]]-the Caucasian or Russian branch of al-Qaeda-killed 15 people and injured a further 64. |- style="background:lightgreen" |April 26 |50 US Army Rangers and 40 [[Afghan National Army Commando Corps|Afghan commandos]] conducted a raid in a village in Achin District, Nangarhar Province, Afghanistan, that was targeting the headquarters of Abdul Hasib, the leader of ISIL-KP, following a heavy, close-quarter firefight and the help of air support, Abdul Hasib and 34 other ISIL-KP terrorists were killed, 2 Rangers were killed and 1 wounded. |-style="background:cornflowerblue" |May 22 |The [[2017 Manchester Arena bombing|Manchester Arena bombing]] in the [[United Kingdom]] killed 22 and injured 116 people, ISIL claimed responsibility. |- style="background:yellowgreen" |May 23–October 23 |The [[Battle of Marawi]] in the Philippines began after an attempt by the Philippine Army to capture Isnilon Hapilon (believed to be the main ISIL leader in the Philippines) failed, resulting in large groups of terrorists affiliated with ISIL in the Philippines (including [[Ansar Khalifa Philippines]] and the [[Maute group]]) and the [[Bangsamoro Islamic Freedom Fighters|Bangsamoro Islamic Freedom Fighters (BIFF)]] clashing with security forces and overrunning and pillaging areas of the city with the aim of establishing a wilayat in [[Lanao del Sur]] Province with the city as its capitol. Filipino forces soon began a counteroffensive, with support from the US, Australia, China and other groups; on 16 October they killed Isnilon Hapilon, the leader of the ASG and Omar Maute, the leader of the Maute group; a week later Filipino forces liberated all ISIL-occupied areas of the city. Between 920 and 962 terrorists were killed and at least 11 captured, whilst Filipino forces lost 165 killed over 1,400 wounded. |- style="background:white" |May 27 |The ASL announced it was formally dissolving itself amid heavy losses that wiped out most of its leadership and decimated its fighters. |- style="background:khaki" |June 6–October 17 |The [[Battle of Raqqa (2017)]] as part of the Raqqa campaign (2016–2017) takes place: Syrian Democratic Forces, supported by coalition forces, fought heavily with ISIL terrorists to successfully liberated the city of Raqqa, which was used as ISIL de facto capital for its caliphate and its headquarters in Syria. The success of the battle of the Raqqa campaign brought it to an end, having liberated the entire Governorate. Between at least 101 to 626 Syrian Democratic forces and coalition troops were killed, across the entire campaign roughly between 4,000 and 5,000 ISIL terrorists were killed and over 700 captured. |- style="background:khaki" |June 7 |The [[2017 Tehran attacks|Tehran attacks]] took place when ISIL terrorists attacked the [[Islamic Consultative Assembly|Iranian Parliament]] building and the [[Mausoleum of Ruhollah Khomeini]] in [[Tehran]], [[Iran]], killing 18 civilians dead and injuring a further 52, 5 terrorists were killed. |- style="background:lightgreen" |July 11 |A US airstrike on an ISIL-KP headquarters in [[Kunar province]], Afghanistan, killed Abu Sayed, the leader of ISIL-KP, along with other ISIL-KP terrorists. |- style="background:khaki" |July 14–October 21 |The [[Central Syria campaign (2017)|Central Syria campaign]] takes place: Pro-Syrian government, Iranian and Russian forces launch the campaign to capture {{convert|11,000|km2|sqmi|order=flip}} of ISIL-occupied territory in central Syria (southern Raqqa Governorate, eastern and northern Homs Governorate, eastern Hama Governorate, northwestern and southwestern Deir ez-Zor Governorate); by 9 September, the combined force ended the Siege of Deir ez-Zor (2014–17). By October 21, the combined force completed the campaign having liberated {{convert|17,000|km2|sqmi|order=flip}} of territory. At least 1,394 terrorists were killed; the combined force lost 929 killed. |- style="background:khaki" |Mid-July |The Battle of Mosul (2016–17) ends in a decisive Iraqi, Kurdish and Coalition forces victory after successfully liberate the city from ISIL control. The city was the terrorists group's last urban strategic stronghold and largest city under its control in Iraq; as well as ending the groups territorial dominance over large areas of northwestern Iraq, it also effectively contained the group's military operations to Syria. Between over 3,000 to at least 16,467 terrorists were killed; Iraqi government forces, Kurdish, coalition, Iranian, Hezbollah and Ba'athists forces lost between 1,235 and over 1,435 killed, as well as 6,090 to over 7,120 wounded. |- style="background:khaki" |July 21–August 28 |The [[Qalamoun offensive (July–August 2017)]] takes place: Syrian forces loyal to Bashar al-Assad, [[Hezbollah]] and [[Lebanese Armed Forces|Lebanese forces]] with US support launched an offensive against HTS and the ISIL terroirsts occupying the [[Lebanon–Syria border]], as well as the Syrian rebel group [[Saraya Ahl al-Sham]]. The offensive succeeded with Lebanese forces and Syrian forces gaining full control of the border for the first time in six years, thus ending the '''[[Syrian Civil War spillover in Lebanon]]'''-on 27 July, a three-day ceasefire agreement was reached by Hezbollah with HTS and Saraya Ahl al-Sham in the Lebanese portion of the [[Qalamoun Mountains]], an agreement resulted in the HTS terrorists to withdraw from Lebanon to [[Idlib]] in Syria, whilst Saraya Ahl al-Sham forces withdrew to the eastern Qalamoun Mountains. After the forces seized much of the border from ISIL terrorists following intense clashes the remnants of ISIL agreed to withdraw to Abu Kamal in Syria-marking the first time that such a large group of ISIL terrorists had agreed to a surrender deal instead of fighting to the death. At least 150 HTS terrorists were killed and 20 ISIL terrorists were killed with a further 100 captured, whilst Hezbollah terrorists lost at least 35 killed and Lebanese forces lost 3 killed. |- style="background:lightgreen" |August 21 |Operation Khyber in Pakistan ended (following the subsidiary Operation Khyber-4) in a Pakistani victory having completely clearing the Khyber Agency and returning it to government control, with terrorist and militant networks destroyed and many of its members either being killed or fleeing the area. |- style="background:khaki" |September 14–December 17 |The [[Eastern Syria campaign (September–December 2017)]] takes place in Deir ez-Zor Governorate: pro-Syrian government, Russian and Iranian forces, with Hezbollah terrorists and other allied militias, [[2017 Mayadin offensive|liberated Mayadin (which ISIL had made its new de facto capital)]] by October 17, [[Battle of Deir ez-Zor (September–November 2017)|cleared the city of Deir ez-Zor]] by November 17 of any remaining ISIL terrorists, as well as [[2017 Abu Kamal offensive|liberate the border town of Abu Kamal]] two days later. The combined force lost over 601 killed, whilst the terrorists lost over 985 killed. |- style="background:lightgreen" |October 18 |A U.S. drone strike in Paktia province, Afghanistan, killed Omar Khalid Khorasani, the leader of the JuA, and 9 other terrorists. |- style="background:khaki" |October 26–December 9 |The [[2017 Western Iraq campaign]] takes place which successfully liberated western Al Anbar Governorate and the remaining [[Upper Mesopotamia|al-Jazira Desert]] (Parts of Nineveh Governorate, Salahuddin Governorate and Anbar Governorate) from ISIL-occupation, thus expelling the terrorists from their last strongholds in Iraq. |- style="background:orangered" |November 24 |ISIL-SP terrorists carried out the [[2017 Sinai mosque attack|Sinai mosque attack]] in [[Al-Rawda, North Sinai|Al-Rawda]] and [[Bir al-Abed]] in [[North Sinai Governorate]], Egypt, killing 311 people and injuring at least 122. |}
==2018== {| class="wikitable" |- ! Dates !! Events |- style="background:lightgrey" |January 19 |Presenting a new [[National Military Strategy (United States)|national defense strategy]], the [[United States Secretary of Defense]], [[Jim Mattis]], says [[terrorism]] is no longer the focus of the [[national security of the United States]]. Now it is [[competition]] between [[List of modern great powers|great powers]]. |- style="background:khaki" |June 18–July 31 |The [[2018 Southern Syria offensive|Southern Syria offensive]] takes place: Pro-Syrian government forces, with Russian and Iranian forces, along with various militias, recaptured [[Daraa Governorate]], Western [[Suwayda Governorate]] and [[Quneitra Governorate]] from Syrian rebels, other rebel factions, ISIL and HTS terrorists. The combined force lost over 300 killed; Rebel forces and HTS lost over 200 killed, whilst ISIL lost 310 killed and between 150 and 200 captured. |}
